const POLITY_CHAPTERS = [{"id":"ch_1","title":"CHAPTER 1","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_2","title":"Company Rule and Early Regulatory Acts (1773–1853)","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_3","title":"1.1 The East India Company and the Need for Regulation","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The British East India Company was established in 1600 under a Royal Charter granted by Queen Elizabeth I. Initially, the Company was a purely commercial enterprise engaged in trade with the East Indi"},{"type":"normal","text":"The constitutional history of India under British rule can be broadly divided into two phases: the Company Rule (1773–1858), during which the British Parliament progressively regulated and controlled "}]},{"id":"sec_4","title":"1.2 The Regulating Act of 1773","level":2,"paras":[]},{"id":"sub_5","title":"1.2.1 Background and Context","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"By the early 1770s, the East India Company was on the verge of bankruptcy despite its territorial gains in India. The Company’s servants were engaged in private trade and personal enrichment at the ex"}]},{"id":"sub_6","title":"1.2.2 Key Provisions of the Regulating Act of 1773","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Regulating Act of 1773 was the first step taken by the British Parliament to regulate the affairs of the East India Company in India. It was also the first step towards centralised administration "},{"type":"normal","text":"First, the Act designated the Governor of Bengal as the Governor-General of Bengal, with supervisory authority over the Presidencies of Madras (now Chennai) and Bombay (now Mumbai) in matters of war a"},{"type":"normal","text":"Second, the Act established a Supreme Court at Calcutta (now Kolkata) in 1774, consisting of a Chief Justice and three other judges. Sir Elijah Impey was appointed as the first Chief Justice. The Supr"},{"type":"normal","text":"Third, the Act prohibited the servants of the Company from engaging in any private trade or accepting presents or bribes from the ‘natives.’ This was an important anti-corruption measure, though enfor"},{"type":"normal","text":"Fourth, the Court of Directors of the Company was required to report on its revenue, civil, and military affairs in India to the British Government. This established the principle of Parliamentary ove"}]},{"id":"sec_7","title":"1.3 Pitt’s India Act of 1784","level":2,"paras":[]},{"id":"sub_8","title":"1.3.1 Background","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Regulating Act of 1773 failed to resolve the problems of Company governance in India. The dual government system persisted, corruption continued, and the relationship between the Supreme Court and"}]},{"id":"sub_9","title":"1.3.2 Key Provisions","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Pitt’s India Act of 1784 established a system of dual control (also called double government) over the Company’s affairs in India. Under this system, the Company’s commercial functions were separated "},{"type":"normal","text":"First, the Act established a Board of Control consisting of six members, including the Chancellor of the Exchequer, a Secretary of State, and four Privy Councillors appointed by the Crown. The Board o"},{"type":"normal","text":"Second, the Court of Directors continued to manage the commercial affairs of the Company. However, it was now subordinate to the Board of Control in all matters relating to civil, military, and revenu"},{"type":"normal","text":"Third, the Act reduced the Governor-General’s Council from four members to three, making it easier for the Governor-General to secure a majority. The Governor-General was given greater authority and c"},{"type":"normal","text":"Fourth, the Presidencies of Bombay and Madras were made subordinate to the Governor-General in Council in all matters (not just war and peace, as under the Regulating Act). This was an important step "},{"type":"normal","text":"Fifth, the Act introduced the concept of a secret committee of three Directors who could transmit secret orders from the Board of Control to India without the knowledge of the full Court of Directors."},{"type":"normal","text":"Sixth, the Company’s Indian territories were for the first time described as ‘British possessions in India,’ thereby establishing British sovereignty over these territories rather than treating them a"}]},{"id":"sec_10","title":"1.4 The Charter Acts (1793, 1813, 1833, 1853)","level":2,"paras":[]},{"id":"sub_11","title":"1.4.1 Charter Act of 1793","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Charter Act of 1793 renewed the East India Company’s charter for a further 20 years. Its important provisions included the following: First, it gave the Governor-General the power to override his "}]},{"id":"sub_12","title":"1.4.2 Charter Act of 1813","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Charter Act of 1813 was a significant milestone in several respects. First, it ended the Company’s monopoly over trade with India, opening the Indian market to all British merchants (though the Co"}]},{"id":"sub_13","title":"1.4.3 Charter Act of 1833","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Charter Act of 1833 is one of the most important Acts in Indian constitutional history. Its provisions are frequently tested in UPSC Prelims. First, it made the Governor-General of Bengal the Gove"}]},{"id":"sub_14","title":"1.4.4 Charter Act of 1853","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Charter Act of 1853 was the last of the Charter Acts and introduced several important reforms. First, it separated the legislative and executive functions of the Governor-General’s Council for the"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: Charter Acts – Comparison"}]},{"id":"ch_15","title":"CHAPTER 2","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_16","title":"Crown Rule: Government of India Acts (1858–1935)","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_17","title":"2.1 Government of India Act of 1858","level":2,"paras":[]},{"id":"sub_18","title":"2.1.1 Background: The Revolt of 1857","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Revolt of 1857 (also known as the First War of Indian Independence, the Sepoy Mutiny, or the Great Rebellion) was a watershed moment in Indian history. Beginning as a mutiny among sepoys of the Be"}]},{"id":"sub_19","title":"2.1.2 Key Provisions of the Act of 1858","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Government of India Act of 1858, also known as the Act for the Better Government of India, transferred the governance of India from the East India Company to the British Crown. The Act ended the d"},{"type":"normal","text":"First, the Company’s rule was abolished and the governance of India was transferred directly to the British Crown, to be exercised through a Secretary of State for India (a member of the British Cabin"},{"type":"normal","text":"Second, the Governor-General of India was re-designated as the Viceroy of India, who was to be the direct representative of the British Crown in India. Lord Canning was the first Viceroy of India (he "},{"type":"normal","text":"Third, the Act abolished the Board of Control and the Court of Directors, both of which had been created by Pitt’s India Act. Fourth, a Council of India with 15 members was created to assist the Secre"}]},{"id":"sec_20","title":"2.2 Indian Councils Act of 1861","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Indian Councils Act of 1861 was the first significant legislative reform after the Crown took over the governance of India. It was introduced to allow some Indian participation in the legislative "}]},{"id":"sec_21","title":"2.3 Indian Councils Act of 1892","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Indian Councils Act of 1892 was passed in response to growing Indian demands for political participation, particularly from the Indian National Congress (founded in 1885). The Act introduced two s"}]},{"id":"sec_22","title":"2.4 Indian Councils Act of 1909 (Morley-Minto Reforms)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Indian Councils Act of 1909, commonly known as the Morley-Minto Reforms (after the Secretary of State Lord Morley and the Viceroy Lord Minto), significantly expanded Indian participation in govern"}]},{"id":"sec_23","title":"2.5 Government of India Act of 1919 (Montagu-Chelmsford Reforms)","level":2,"paras":[]},{"id":"sub_24","title":"2.5.1 Background","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The First World War (1914–1918) created enormous political pressure for reform. India contributed over a million soldiers and massive financial resources to the war effort. In August 1917, Secretary o"}]},{"id":"sub_25","title":"2.5.2 Key Provisions","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"First, the Act introduced dyarchy (dual government) in the provinces. Provincial subjects were divided into two categories: ‘transferred subjects’ and ‘reserved subjects.’ Transferred subjects (such a"},{"type":"normal","text":"Second, the Act introduced bicameralism at the Centre for the first time. The Indian Legislative Council was replaced by a bicameral legislature consisting of the Council of State (Upper House) and th"},{"type":"normal","text":"Third, the Act extended the principle of communal representation to Sikhs, Indian Christians, Anglo-Indians, and Europeans, in addition to Muslims (who had received separate electorates in 1909). This"},{"type":"normal","text":"Fourth, the Act established the office of the High Commissioner for India in London to represent Indian interests. Fifth, the Act provided for the establishment of a Public Service Commission in India"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: Dyarchy under GoI Act 1919"}]},{"id":"sec_26","title":"2.6 Simon Commission (1927)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Government of India Act of 1919 provided for a statutory commission to review the working of the Act after 10 years. However, Lord Birkenhead, the Secretary of State, advanced this review and appo"}]},{"id":"sec_27","title":"2.7 Government of India Act of 1935","level":2,"paras":[]},{"id":"sub_28","title":"2.7.1 Background","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Government of India Act of 1935 was the outcome of a long process that included the Simon Commission Report (1930), the three Round Table Conferences (1930, 1931, 1932), the Communal Award by the "}]},{"id":"sub_29","title":"2.7.2 Key Provisions","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"First, the Act proposed an All-India Federation consisting of British Indian provinces and princely states. This was the first time the concept of an Indian federation was formally proposed. However, "},{"type":"normal","text":"Second, the Act abolished dyarchy in the provinces and introduced provincial autonomy. The provinces were granted autonomous status with responsible government. The Governor was to act on the advice o"},{"type":"normal","text":"Third, the Act introduced dyarchy at the Centre (in place of provincial dyarchy under the 1919 Act). Federal subjects were divided into ‘reserved’ subjects (defence, external affairs, ecclesiastical a"},{"type":"normal","text":"Fourth, the Act introduced bicameralism in six provinces (Bengal, Bombay, Madras, Bihar, Assam, and the United Provinces). These provinces had a Legislative Council (Upper House) and a Legislative Ass"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: Evolution of British Constitutional Acts"}]},{"id":"ch_30","title":"CHAPTER 3","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_31","title":"Towards Independence: Cabinet Mission and Mountbatten Plan","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_32","title":"3.1 The Cripps Mission (1942)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"In March 1942, during the Second World War, the British Government sent Sir Stafford Cripps to India with proposals to secure Indian cooperation in the war effort. The Cripps Mission proposed that Ind"}]},{"id":"sec_33","title":"3.2 The Cabinet Mission Plan (1946)","level":2,"paras":[]},{"id":"sub_34","title":"3.2.1 Background","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"After the end of the Second World War in 1945, the Labour Government under Prime Minister Clement Attlee came to power in Britain. Attlee was sympathetic to Indian demands for independence. In Februar"}]},{"id":"sub_35","title":"3.2.2 Key Recommendations","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"First, the Cabinet Mission rejected the demand for a separate sovereign state of Pakistan, stating that the creation of Pakistan would not solve the communal problem, as there would still be significa"},{"type":"normal","text":"Second, the Mission proposed the creation of a Union of India comprising both British India and the princely states. The Union would deal with foreign affairs, defence, and communications, and would h"},{"type":"normal","text":"Third, the provinces were to be divided into three groups: Group A (Madras, Bombay, United Provinces, Bihar, Central Provinces, and Orissa – Hindu-majority provinces); Group B (Punjab, North-West Fron"},{"type":"normal","text":"Fourth, and most importantly, the Mission proposed the formation of a Constituent Assembly to frame a new constitution for India. The Constituent Assembly was to be indirectly elected by the members o"}]},{"id":"sec_36","title":"3.3 The Mountbatten Plan (3 June 1947) and Indian Independence Act, 1947","level":2,"paras":[]},{"id":"sub_37","title":"3.3.1 Background","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"By early 1947, communal violence had escalated sharply, particularly after the Direct Action Day called by the Muslim League on 16 August 1946, which led to the Great Calcutta Killings. Lord Mountbatt"}]},{"id":"sub_38","title":"3.3.2 The Indian Independence Act, 1947","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Indian Independence Act, 1947 was passed by the British Parliament on 18 July 1947. It gave legal effect to the Mountbatten Plan and contained the following key provisions:"},{"type":"normal","text":"First, the Act created two independent Dominions – India and Pakistan – with effect from 15 August 1947. Second, the Act provided for the partition of Bengal and Punjab between the two new Dominions, "},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: Key Events Leading to Independence"},{"type":"normal","text":"PART II"},{"type":"normal","text":"MAKING OF THE CONSTITUTION"}]},{"id":"ch_39","title":"CHAPTER 4","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_40","title":"The Constituent Assembly","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_41","title":"4.1 Formation of the Constituent Assembly","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The idea of a Constituent Assembly for India was first put forward by M.N. Roy, a pioneer of the communist movement in India, in 1934. The Indian National Congress officially demanded a Constituent As"},{"type":"normal","text":"After the partition of India under the Mountbatten Plan, the representatives of the areas that became Pakistan (including East Bengal, West Punjab, Sindh, North-West Frontier Province, Baluchistan, Sy"}]},{"id":"sub_42","title":"4.1.1 Key Sessions of the Constituent Assembly","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The first session of the Constituent Assembly was held on 9 December 1946 in the Constitution Hall (now known as the Central Hall of Parliament). Dr. Sachchidananda Sinha was elected as the temporary "},{"type":"normal","text":"The Muslim League boycotted the Constituent Assembly from the beginning, and the representatives of most princely states did not initially participate. After the Indian Independence Act of 1947, the M"}]},{"id":"sec_43","title":"4.2 The Drafting Committee","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"On 29 August 1947, the Constituent Assembly set up a Drafting Committee under the chairmanship of Dr. B.R. Ambedkar to prepare a Draft Constitution. The Drafting Committee had seven members: Dr. B.R. "},{"type":"normal","text":"The Constituent Assembly also had several other important committees, including the Union Powers Committee (chaired by Jawaharlal Nehru), the Union Constitution Committee (chaired by Jawaharlal Nehru)"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: Major Committees of Constituent Assembly"}]},{"id":"sec_44","title":"4.3 Functions of the Constituent Assembly","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Constituent Assembly performed multiple functions beyond constitution-making. First, it functioned as the first Parliament of independent India. From 15 August 1947 to 26 January 1950, the Constit"}]},{"id":"sec_45","title":"4.4 Constitutional Philosophy and the Objectives Resolution","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Objectives Resolution, moved by Jawaharlal Nehru on 13 December 1946, laid down the fundamental principles and philosophy of the Constitution. The Resolution declared that India shall be an Indepe"}]},{"id":"sec_46","title":"4.5 Sources of the Indian Constitution","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Indian Constitution is not an original document in the sense that every provision was freshly conceived. The framers drew extensively from the constitutional experience of other countries, adaptin"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: Sources of the Indian Constitution"}]},{"id":"sec_47","title":"4.6 Criticism of the Constituent Assembly","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Constituent Assembly has been criticised on several grounds. First, it was not elected on the basis of universal adult franchise; the members were chosen indirectly by provincial legislatures that"}]},{"id":"sec_48","title":"4.7 The Enactment Clause and the Significance of November 26","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Constitution begins with the words: ‘WE, THE PEOPLE OF INDIA, having solemnly resolved to constitute India into a SOVEREIGN SOCIALIST SECULAR DEMOCRATIC REPUBLIC...’ (with the words ‘Socialist’ an"},{"type":"normal","text":"PART III"},{"type":"normal","text":"SALIENT FEATURES OF THE INDIAN CONSTITUTION"}]},{"id":"ch_49","title":"CHAPTER 5","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_50","title":"Salient Features of the Constitution","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_51","title":"5.1 The Lengthiest Written Constitution in the World","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Indian Constitution is the longest written constitution of any sovereign country in the world. In its original form, it had 395 articles divided into 22 parts and 8 schedules. As of 2024, the Cons"}]},{"id":"sec_52","title":"5.2 Drawn from Various Sources","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"As discussed in detail in Part II, the Indian Constitution draws from the constitutional experience of many countries. However, the structural scheme and a large number of provisions are derived from "}]},{"id":"sec_53","title":"5.3 Blend of Rigidity and Flexibility","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Indian Constitution is neither wholly rigid (like the US Constitution) nor wholly flexible (like the British Constitution). It combines elements of both. Article 368 provides for the amendment of "}]},{"id":"sec_54","title":"5.4 Federal System with Unitary Bias","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Indian Constitution establishes a federal system of government with a strong unitary bias. Federal features include: a written Constitution, division of powers between the Centre and States (throu"}]},{"id":"sec_55","title":"5.5 Parliamentary Form of Government","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Constitution establishes a parliamentary form of government at both the Centre and in the States, based on the British (Westminster) model. The features of the Indian parliamentary system include:"}]},{"id":"sec_56","title":"5.6 Synthesis of Parliamentary Sovereignty and Judicial Supremacy","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Unlike Britain (where Parliament is supreme and its laws cannot be challenged in court) and unlike the United States (where the Supreme Court has supremacy through judicial review), the Indian Constit"}]},{"id":"sec_57","title":"5.7 Integrated and Independent Judiciary","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Indian Constitution provides for a single integrated judicial system with the Supreme Court at the apex, followed by the High Courts at the state level, and subordinate courts at the district and "}]},{"id":"sec_58","title":"5.8 Fundamental Rights","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Part III of the Constitution (Articles 12–35) guarantees six categories of Fundamental Rights: Right to Equality (Articles 14–18), Right to Freedom (Articles 19–22), Right Against Exploitation (Articl"}]},{"id":"sec_59","title":"5.9 Directive Principles of State Policy","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Part IV of the Constitution (Articles 36–51) contains the Directive Principles of State Policy (DPSP), which are guidelines for the government to establish a just and welfare society. The DPSPs are in"}]},{"id":"sec_60","title":"5.10 Fundamental Duties","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Part IVA of the Constitution (Article 51A) contains the Fundamental Duties of citizens. These were added by the 42nd Amendment Act of 1976 on the recommendation of the Swaran Singh Committee. Original"}]},{"id":"sec_61","title":"5.11 Secular State","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"India is a secular state. While the word ‘Secular’ was explicitly added to the Preamble by the 42nd Amendment Act of 1976, the Constitution was secular in character from its inception. The Indian conc"}]},{"id":"sec_62","title":"5.12 Universal Adult Franchise","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Article 326 of the Constitution provides for universal adult franchise. Every citizen of India who has attained the age of 18 years (originally 21 years; reduced to 18 by the 61st Amendment Act of 198"}]},{"id":"sec_63","title":"5.13 Single Citizenship","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Unlike the United States, which has a dual citizenship system (federal and state), India follows the principle of single citizenship. Every citizen of India is a citizen of India and only of India, re"}]},{"id":"sec_64","title":"5.14 Independent Bodies","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Constitution establishes several independent bodies to ensure the smooth functioning of democracy. These include the Election Commission of India (Article 324), the Comptroller and Auditor General"}]},{"id":"sec_65","title":"5.15 Emergency Provisions","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Constitution contains detailed emergency provisions (Articles 352–360) that can transform the federal structure into a virtually unitary one during times of crisis. Three types of emergencies are "}]},{"id":"sec_66","title":"5.16 Three-Tier Government","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The original Constitution provided for a two-tier system of government: the Union and the States. The 73rd and 74th Amendment Acts of 1992 added a third tier by constitutionalising local self-governme"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: Salient Features at a Glance"},{"type":"normal","text":"PART IV"},{"type":"normal","text":"THE PREAMBLE TO THE CONSTITUTION"}]},{"id":"ch_67","title":"CHAPTER 6","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_68","title":"The Preamble","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_69","title":"6.1 Text of the Preamble","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Preamble to the Constitution of India reads: ‘WE, THE PEOPLE OF INDIA, having solemnly resolved to constitute India into a SOVEREIGN SOCIALIST SECULAR DEMOCRATIC REPUBLIC and to secure to all its "}]},{"id":"sec_70","title":"6.2 Key Concepts in the Preamble","level":2,"paras":[]},{"id":"sub_71","title":"6.2.1 Sovereign","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The word ‘Sovereign’ means that India has supreme authority over its internal and external affairs. Internally, no authority is above the Constitution and the elected government. Externally, India is "}]},{"id":"sub_72","title":"6.2.2 Socialist","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The word ‘Socialist’ was added to the Preamble by the 42nd Amendment Act of 1976. Indian socialism is not the rigid Marxist socialism of state ownership of all means of production. Rather, it refers t"}]},{"id":"sub_73","title":"6.2.3 Secular","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The word ‘Secular’ was also added by the 42nd Amendment Act of 1976. As discussed earlier, Indian secularism means equal treatment of all religions by the State. The State does not have an official re"}]},{"id":"sub_74","title":"6.2.4 Democratic","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"India is a democratic state where the government derives its authority from the will of the people. The Constitution provides for representative democracy (indirect democracy) through regular election"}]},{"id":"sub_75","title":"6.2.5 Republic","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"A republic is a form of government where the head of state is elected (directly or indirectly) and is not a hereditary monarch. In India, the President is the head of state and is elected indirectly b"}]},{"id":"sub_76","title":"6.2.6 Justice","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Preamble aims to secure justice in three dimensions: social justice (equal treatment of all citizens without any social discrimination based on caste, colour, race, religion, sex, etc.), economic "}]},{"id":"sub_77","title":"6.2.7 Liberty","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Preamble guarantees liberty of thought, expression, belief, faith, and worship. Liberty is essential for the development of individual personality and the functioning of democracy. The concept of "}]},{"id":"sub_78","title":"6.2.8 Equality","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Preamble secures equality of status and of opportunity. Equality of status means the absence of special privileges and equal treatment under the law (ensured by Articles 14–18). Equality of opport"}]},{"id":"sub_79","title":"6.2.9 Fraternity","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Preamble seeks to promote fraternity among all citizens, assuring the dignity of the individual and the unity and integrity of the nation. The word ‘integrity’ was added by the 42nd Amendment Act "}]},{"id":"sec_80","title":"6.3 Is the Preamble a Part of the Constitution?","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The question of whether the Preamble is a part of the Constitution has been settled through judicial interpretation. In the Berubari Union case (1960), the Supreme Court held that the Preamble is NOT "},{"type":"normal","text":"However, the Preamble is NOT enforceable in a court of law, meaning no law can be struck down solely because it violates the Preamble. The Preamble is not a source of power for the legislature or the "}]},{"id":"sec_81","title":"6.4 Can the Preamble be Amended?","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Preamble can be amended under Article 368, subject to the condition that no amendment shall destroy the basic structure of the Constitution. This was established in the Kesavananda Bharati case (1"},{"type":"normal","text":"PART V"},{"type":"normal","text":"CITIZENSHIP"}]},{"id":"ch_82","title":"CHAPTER 7","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_83","title":"Citizenship (Articles 5–11)","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_84","title":"7.1 Constitutional Provisions on Citizenship","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Citizenship is dealt with in Articles 5 to 11 in Part II of the Constitution. These articles deal with citizenship at the commencement of the Constitution (26 January 1950). They do not deal with the "}]},{"id":"sub_85","title":"7.1.1 Article 5 – Citizenship at the Commencement of the Constitution","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Article 5 provides that every person who had his domicile in the territory of India and who was born in the territory of India, or either of whose parents was born in the territory of India, or who ha"}]},{"id":"sub_86","title":"7.1.2 Article 6 – Rights of Persons Who Migrated to India from Pakistan","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Article 6 deals with persons who migrated to India from the territories that became part of Pakistan. Such a person is deemed to be a citizen of India if: (a) he or either of his parents or grandparen"}]},{"id":"sub_87","title":"7.1.3 Article 7 – Rights of Persons Who Migrated to Pakistan","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Article 7 provides that a person who migrated to Pakistan after 1 March 1947 shall not be deemed to be a citizen of India. However, if such a person returned to India under a permit for resettlement o"}]},{"id":"sub_88","title":"7.1.4 Article 8 – Persons of Indian Origin Residing Outside India","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Article 8 provides that any person who or either of whose parents or grandparents was born in India (as defined in the Government of India Act 1935) and who is ordinarily residing in any country outsi"}]},{"id":"sub_89","title":"7.1.5 Articles 9, 10, and 11","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Article 9 provides that any person who has voluntarily acquired the citizenship of a foreign state shall not be a citizen of India. This reinforces the principle of single citizenship. Article 10 prov"}]},{"id":"sec_90","title":"7.2 The Citizenship Act, 1955","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Citizenship Act of 1955, enacted under Article 11, prescribes five modes of acquiring Indian citizenship: by birth, by descent, by registration, by naturalisation, and by incorporation of territor"}]},{"id":"sub_91","title":"7.2.1 Acquisition by Birth (Section 3)","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"A person born in India on or after 26 January 1950 but before 1 July 1987 is a citizen of India by birth, irrespective of the nationality of the parents (jus soli). A person born in India on or after "}]},{"id":"sub_92","title":"7.2.2 Acquisition by Descent (Section 4)","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"A person born outside India on or after 26 January 1950 but before 10 December 1992 is a citizen of India by descent if his father was a citizen of India at the time of birth. A person born outside In"}]},{"id":"sub_93","title":"7.2.3 Acquisition by Registration (Section 5)","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Central Government may, on application, register as a citizen of India any person who is not an illegal migrant and falls into certain categories: persons of Indian origin who are ordinarily resid"}]},{"id":"sub_94","title":"7.2.4 Acquisition by Naturalisation (Section 6)","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Central Government may, on application, grant a certificate of naturalisation to any person who is not an illegal migrant and satisfies certain qualifications specified in the Third Schedule of th"}]},{"id":"sub_95","title":"7.2.5 Loss of Citizenship","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Citizenship can be lost in three ways: By Renunciation (Section 8) – any citizen of India of full age and capacity can make a declaration of renunciation. Upon registration of the declaration, that pe"}]},{"id":"sec_96","title":"7.3 Overseas Citizenship of India (OCI)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Citizenship (Amendment) Act of 2005 introduced the concept of Overseas Citizenship of India (OCI). OCI is not full Indian citizenship. An OCI cardholder is not a citizen of India and does not enjo"},{"type":"normal","text":"PART VI"},{"type":"normal","text":"FUNDAMENTAL RIGHTS"}]},{"id":"ch_97","title":"CHAPTER 8","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_98","title":"Fundamental Rights (Articles 12–35)","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_99","title":"8.1 Introduction and Nature of Fundamental Rights","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Part III of the Constitution (Articles 12–35) is called the ‘Magna Carta’ of India. It guarantees six categories of Fundamental Rights to all citizens (and some to all persons, including foreigners). "},{"type":"normal","text":"Fundamental Rights operate as limitations on the power of the State (defined in Article 12) and protect individuals against arbitrary state action. They are available against the State, not against pr"}]},{"id":"sec_100","title":"8.2 Definition of ‘State’ (Article 12)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Article 12 defines the term ‘State’ for the purposes of Part III. The ‘State’ includes: (a) the Government and Parliament of India (i.e., the Union Executive and Legislature); (b) the Government and L"}]},{"id":"sec_101","title":"8.3 Laws Inconsistent with Fundamental Rights (Article 13)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Article 13 declares that all laws that are inconsistent with or in derogation of any of the Fundamental Rights shall be void to the extent of the inconsistency. Article 13(1) provides that all pre-con"},{"type":"normal","text":"The doctrine of eclipse and the doctrine of severability are two important judicial doctrines that have developed under Article 13. The doctrine of eclipse holds that a pre-constitutional law that is "}]},{"id":"sec_102","title":"8.4 Right to Equality (Articles 14–18)","level":2,"paras":[]},{"id":"sub_103","title":"8.4.1 Article 14 – Equality Before the Law and Equal Protection of the Laws","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Article 14 provides that ‘The State shall not deny to any person equality before the law or the equal protection of the laws within the territory of India.’ This article embodies two distinct concepts"}]},{"id":"sub_104","title":"8.4.2 Article 15 – Prohibition of Discrimination","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Article 15(1) provides that the State shall not discriminate against any citizen on grounds only of religion, race, caste, sex, or place of birth. Article 15(2) extends this prohibition to private ind"}]},{"id":"sub_105","title":"8.4.3 Article 16 – Equality of Opportunity in Public Employment","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Article 16(1) guarantees equality of opportunity for all citizens in matters relating to employment or appointment to any office under the State. Article 16(2) prohibits discrimination on grounds of r"}]},{"id":"sub_106","title":"8.4.4 Article 17 – Abolition of Untouchability","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Article 17 abolishes ‘untouchability’ and forbids its practice in any form. The enforcement of any disability arising out of untouchability is an offence punishable in accordance with law. Parliament "}]},{"id":"sub_107","title":"8.4.5 Article 18 – Abolition of Titles","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Article 18(1) provides that the State shall not confer any title that is not a military or academic distinction. Article 18(2) provides that no citizen of India shall accept any title from any foreign"}]},{"id":"sec_108","title":"8.5 Right to Freedom (Articles 19–22)","level":2,"paras":[]},{"id":"sub_109","title":"8.5.1 Article 19 – Protection of Six Rights","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Article 19(1) guarantees six freedoms to citizens of India: (a) freedom of speech and expression; (b) freedom to assemble peaceably and without arms; (c) freedom to form associations or unions or coop"},{"type":"normal","text":"Article 19(2) allows the State to impose reasonable restrictions on freedom of speech and expression in the interests of: sovereignty and integrity of India, security of the State, friendly relations "}]},{"id":"sub_110","title":"8.5.2 Article 20 – Protection in Respect of Conviction for Offences","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Article 20 provides three protections against arbitrary conviction. Article 20(1) provides that no person shall be convicted of any offence except for violation of a law in force at the time of the co"}]},{"id":"sub_111","title":"8.5.3 Article 21 – Protection of Life and Personal Liberty","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Article 21 provides: ‘No person shall be deprived of his life or personal liberty except according to procedure established by law.’ This is the most litigated and most expansively interpreted article"}]},{"id":"sub_112","title":"8.5.4 Article 21A – Right to Education","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Article 21A was inserted by the 86th Amendment Act of 2002. It provides: ‘The State shall provide free and compulsory education to all children of the age of six to fourteen years in such manner as th"}]},{"id":"sub_113","title":"8.5.5 Article 22 – Protection Against Arrest and Detention","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Article 22 provides protection to persons who are arrested or detained. Article 22(1) provides that every arrested person has the right to be informed of the grounds of arrest, the right to consult an"}]},{"id":"sec_114","title":"8.6 Right Against Exploitation (Articles 23–24)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Article 23 prohibits traffic in human beings, begar (forced labour), and other similar forms of forced labour. Any contravention of this provision is an offence punishable in accordance with law. Howe"}]},{"id":"sec_115","title":"8.7 Right to Freedom of Religion (Articles 25–28)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Article 25 guarantees to all persons the freedom of conscience and the right to freely profess, practise, and propagate religion, subject to public order, morality, and health. Article 25(2) allows th"}]},{"id":"sec_116","title":"8.8 Cultural and Educational Rights (Articles 29–30)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Article 29(1) provides that any section of the citizens residing in India having a distinct language, script, or culture shall have the right to conserve the same. Article 29(2) provides that no citiz"}]},{"id":"sec_117","title":"8.9 Right to Constitutional Remedies (Articles 32–35)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Article 32 guarantees the right to move the Supreme Court for the enforcement of Fundamental Rights. Dr. B.R. Ambedkar called Article 32 the ‘heart and soul’ of the Constitution. The Supreme Court (un"}]},{"id":"sub_118","title":"8.9.1 Habeas Corpus","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Habeas corpus literally means ‘to have the body.’ This writ is issued to produce a person who has been detained or imprisoned before the court to examine the legality of the detention. It can be issue"}]},{"id":"sub_119","title":"8.9.2 Mandamus","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Mandamus literally means ‘we command.’ It is issued by a court to a public authority directing it to perform its legal duty that it has failed or refused to perform. Mandamus can be issued against any"}]},{"id":"sub_120","title":"8.9.3 Prohibition","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The writ of prohibition is issued by a higher court to a lower court or tribunal to prevent the latter from exceeding its jurisdiction or acting contrary to the rules of natural justice. It is availab"}]},{"id":"sub_121","title":"8.9.4 Certiorari","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Certiorari literally means ‘to be certified.’ It is issued by a higher court to a lower court or tribunal to quash its order or decision on the ground that the lower court or tribunal has exceeded its"}]},{"id":"sub_122","title":"8.9.5 Quo Warranto","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Quo warranto literally means ‘by what authority.’ It is issued to inquire into the legality of a person’s claim to a public office. It can be issued only when the office is a public office created by "},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: Five Writs at a Glance"}]},{"id":"sec_123","title":"8.10 Difference Between Articles 32 and 226","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Article 32 empowers the Supreme Court to issue writs for the enforcement of Fundamental Rights only. Article 226 empowers the High Courts to issue writs for the enforcement of Fundamental Rights AND f"},{"type":"normal","text":"PART VII"},{"type":"normal","text":"DIRECTIVE PRINCIPLES OF STATE POLICY"}]},{"id":"ch_124","title":"CHAPTER 9","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_125","title":"Directive Principles (Articles 36–51)","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_126","title":"9.1 Nature and Significance","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Part IV of the Constitution (Articles 36–51) contains the Directive Principles of State Policy (DPSP). These are inspired by the Irish Constitution and represent the socio-economic ideals that the Sta"}]},{"id":"sec_127","title":"9.2 Classification of Directive Principles","level":2,"paras":[]},{"id":"sub_128","title":"9.2.1 Socialistic Principles","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"These principles reflect the socialist ideology and aim to establish a welfare state. Article 38 directs the State to secure a social order for the promotion of the welfare of the people by minimising"}]},{"id":"sub_129","title":"9.2.2 Gandhian Principles","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"These principles are based on the ideals of Mahatma Gandhi. Article 40 directs the State to organise village panchayats and endow them with powers and authority to enable them to function as units of "}]},{"id":"sub_130","title":"9.2.3 Liberal-Intellectual Principles","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"These principles reflect the ideology of liberalism. Article 44 directs the State to secure a Uniform Civil Code throughout the territory of India. Article 45 (as amended by the 86th Amendment, 2002) "}]},{"id":"sec_131","title":"9.3 Conflict Between Fundamental Rights and DPSPs","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The relationship between Fundamental Rights and DPSPs has been one of the most debated issues in Indian constitutional law. The initial position was established in State of Madras v. Champakam Doraira"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: Key DPSPs and Their Articles"},{"type":"normal","text":"PART VIII"},{"type":"normal","text":"FUNDAMENTAL DUTIES"}]},{"id":"ch_132","title":"CHAPTER 10","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_133","title":"Fundamental Duties (Article 51A)","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_134","title":"10.1 Introduction","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Part IVA of the Constitution contains the Fundamental Duties of citizens. These were added by the 42nd Amendment Act of 1976 on the recommendation of the Swaran Singh Committee (1976). Originally, 10 "}]},{"id":"sec_135","title":"10.2 List of 11 Fundamental Duties","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Article 51A provides that it shall be the duty of every citizen of India:"},{"type":"normal","text":"(a) To abide by the Constitution and respect its ideals and institutions, the National Flag and the National Anthem."},{"type":"normal","text":"(b) To cherish and follow the noble ideals which inspired our national struggle for freedom."},{"type":"normal","text":"(c) To uphold and protect the sovereignty, unity and integrity of India."},{"type":"normal","text":"(d) To defend the country and render national service when called upon to do so."},{"type":"normal","text":"(e) To promote harmony and the spirit of common brotherhood amongst all the people of India transcending religious, linguistic and regional or sectional diversities; to renounce practices derogatory t"},{"type":"normal","text":"(f) To value and preserve the rich heritage of our composite culture."},{"type":"normal","text":"(g) To protect and improve the natural environment including forests, lakes, rivers and wildlife, and to have compassion for living creatures."},{"type":"normal","text":"(h) To develop the scientific temper, humanism and the spirit of inquiry and reform."},{"type":"normal","text":"(i) To safeguard public property and to abjure violence."},{"type":"normal","text":"(j) To strive towards excellence in all spheres of individual and collective activity so that the nation constantly rises to higher levels of endeavour and achievement."},{"type":"normal","text":"(k) To provide opportunities for education to his child or, as the case may be, ward between the age of six and fourteen years. (Added by the 86th Amendment, 2002)"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: Comparison: FR vs DPSP vs FD"},{"type":"normal","text":"PART IX"},{"type":"normal","text":"THE UNION EXECUTIVE"}]},{"id":"ch_136","title":"CHAPTER 11","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_137","title":"The President of India (Articles 52–78)","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_138","title":"11.1 Election of the President (Article 54–55)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The President of India is the head of state and the first citizen of India. The President is elected by an electoral college consisting of: (a) the elected members of both Houses of Parliament (Lok Sa"},{"type":"normal","text":"The value of the vote of each MLA is calculated as: (Total population of the State ÷ Total number of elected members of the State Legislative Assembly) × (1/1000). The value of the vote of each MP is "}]},{"id":"sec_139","title":"11.2 Qualifications and Conditions (Articles 58–59)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"To be eligible for election as President, a person must: (a) be a citizen of India; (b) have completed the age of 35 years; (c) be qualified for election as a member of the Lok Sabha; and (d) not hold"}]},{"id":"sec_140","title":"11.3 Term, Impeachment, and Vacancy (Articles 56–62)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The President holds office for a term of five years from the date on which he enters upon his office. He may resign by writing to the Vice President. He can be removed from office by impeachment for ‘"},{"type":"normal","text":"In case of a vacancy due to death, resignation, removal, or otherwise, the Vice President acts as the President. If the Vice President is also unavailable, the Chief Justice of India (or the senior-mo"}]},{"id":"sec_141","title":"11.4 Powers of the President","level":2,"paras":[]},{"id":"sub_142","title":"11.4.1 Executive Powers","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"All executive actions of the Government of India are taken in the name of the President (Article 77). The President appoints the Prime Minister and other members of the Council of Ministers. He appoin"}]},{"id":"sub_143","title":"11.4.2 Legislative Powers","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The President summons and prorogues the sessions of Parliament and can dissolve the Lok Sabha (Article 85). He addresses both Houses of Parliament at the commencement of the first session after each g"}]},{"id":"sub_144","title":"11.4.3 Financial Powers","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"No Money Bill can be introduced in Parliament without the prior recommendation of the President (Article 117). The President causes the Annual Budget to be laid before Parliament. The Contingency Fund"}]},{"id":"sub_145","title":"11.4.4 Judicial Powers","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The President has the power to grant pardons, reprieves, respites, or remissions of punishment, or to suspend, remit, or commute the sentence of any person convicted of any offence under Article 72. T"}]},{"id":"sub_146","title":"11.4.5 Emergency Powers","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The President can proclaim three types of emergencies: National Emergency under Article 352 (on grounds of war, external aggression, or armed rebellion); President’s Rule in a state under Article 356 "}]},{"id":"sub_147","title":"11.4.6 Diplomatic Powers","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"International treaties and agreements are negotiated and concluded in the name of the President. The President represents India in international forums and affairs (though in practice, these functions"}]},{"id":"sec_148","title":"11.5 Veto Powers of the President","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"When a bill is presented to the President for assent, he has three options. First, he may give his assent – the bill then becomes an Act. Second, he may withhold his assent – the bill does not become "},{"type":"normal","text":"For State bills reserved by the Governor for the President’s consideration (under Article 200), the President has three options: give assent, withhold assent, or direct the Governor to return the bill"}]},{"id":"ch_149","title":"CHAPTER 12","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_150","title":"Vice President, Prime Minister, Council of Ministers, and Attorney General","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_151","title":"12.1 The Vice President (Articles 63–71)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Vice President is the second-highest constitutional office in India. He is elected by the members of an electoral college consisting of members of BOTH Houses of Parliament (Lok Sabha and Rajya Sa"},{"type":"normal","text":"The Vice President is the ex officio Chairman of the Rajya Sabha and presides over its sessions. When the Vice President acts as President (in case of vacancy or absence), he ceases to perform the fun"}]},{"id":"sec_152","title":"12.2 The Prime Minister (Articles 74–75)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Prime Minister is the head of government, the real executive, and the most powerful functionary in the Indian political system. Article 74 provides that there shall be a Council of Ministers with "},{"type":"normal","text":"The President appoints the Prime Minister. By convention, the leader of the majority party (or coalition) in the Lok Sabha is appointed as Prime Minister. The Prime Minister need not be a member of th"}]},{"id":"sec_153","title":"12.3 The Council of Ministers (Article 74–75)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Council of Ministers consists of three categories: Cabinet Ministers (who attend Cabinet meetings, hold important portfolios, and participate in policy-making), Ministers of State (who may hold in"}]},{"id":"sec_154","title":"12.4 The Attorney General of India (Article 76)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Attorney General of India is the highest law officer of the Government of India. He is appointed by the President and must be a person who is qualified to be appointed as a judge of the Supreme Co"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: President vs Vice President – Key Differences"},{"type":"normal","text":"PART X"},{"type":"normal","text":"THE PARLIAMENT OF INDIA"}]},{"id":"ch_155","title":"CHAPTER 13","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_156","title":"Parliament: Lok Sabha and Rajya Sabha","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_157","title":"13.1 Composition of Parliament (Article 79)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Article 79 provides that the Parliament of India consists of the President and two Houses: the Council of States (Rajya Sabha) and the House of the People (Lok Sabha). The President is an integral par"}]},{"id":"sec_158","title":"13.2 The Rajya Sabha (Council of States)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Rajya Sabha is the Upper House of Parliament. Its maximum strength is 250 members: 238 elected members representing States and Union Territories, and 12 members nominated by the President from per"}]},{"id":"sec_159","title":"13.3 The Lok Sabha (House of the People)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Lok Sabha is the Lower House of Parliament and is directly elected by the people. Its maximum strength is 550 members: up to 530 elected from States and up to 20 from Union Territories (Article 81"}]},{"id":"sec_160","title":"13.4 Sessions of Parliament","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The President summons each House of Parliament from time to time. The maximum gap between two sessions of Parliament cannot be more than six months. There are normally three sessions in a year: the Bu"}]},{"id":"sec_161","title":"13.5 Legislative Procedure","level":2,"paras":[]},{"id":"sub_162","title":"13.5.1 Ordinary Bills","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"An ordinary bill can be introduced in either House of Parliament. It goes through three readings in each House: First Reading (introduction of the bill), Second Reading (general discussion followed by"}]},{"id":"sub_163","title":"13.5.2 Money Bills (Article 110)","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"A Money Bill can ONLY be introduced in the Lok Sabha, and only with the prior recommendation of the President. After being passed by the Lok Sabha, it is transmitted to the Rajya Sabha for its recomme"}]},{"id":"sub_164","title":"13.5.3 Constitutional Amendment Bills (Article 368)","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"A Constitutional Amendment Bill can be introduced in either House of Parliament. It does not require the President’s prior recommendation. The bill must be passed by each House by a special majority, "}]},{"id":"sec_165","title":"13.6 Parliamentary Committees","level":2,"paras":[]},{"id":"sub_166","title":"13.6.1 Types of Committees","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Parliamentary Committees are of two types: Standing Committees (permanent committees constituted every year or periodically) and Ad Hoc Committees (temporary committees constituted for a specific purp"},{"type":"normal","text":"The Public Accounts Committee (PAC) examines the appropriation accounts of the Government and the audit reports of the Comptroller and Auditor General. It has 22 members (15 from Lok Sabha and 7 from "},{"type":"normal","text":"The Estimates Committee examines the estimates included in the budget and suggests economies in expenditure. It has 30 members, all from the Lok Sabha (Rajya Sabha has no representation). Its Chairman"},{"type":"normal","text":"The Committee on Public Undertakings examines the reports and accounts of public undertakings. It has 22 members (15 from Lok Sabha and 7 from Rajya Sabha). Its Chairman is appointed by the Speaker fr"},{"type":"normal","text":"The Departmentally Related Standing Committees (DRSCs) were established in 1993 (reconstituted in 2004). There are 24 such committees, each dealing with a group of ministries/departments. Each committ"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: Key Parliamentary Committees"}]},{"id":"sec_167","title":"13.7 Parliamentary Privileges","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Members of Parliament enjoy certain privileges and immunities, without which they cannot discharge their functions independently. These include: freedom of speech in Parliament (Article 105 – no membe"},{"type":"normal","text":"PART XI"},{"type":"normal","text":"THE JUDICIARY"}]},{"id":"ch_168","title":"CHAPTER 14","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_169","title":"The Supreme Court of India","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_170","title":"14.1 Composition and Appointment (Articles 124–147)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Supreme Court of India is the apex court of the country. It was inaugurated on 28 January 1950, two days after the Constitution came into effect. Initially, it consisted of a Chief Justice and 7 o"},{"type":"normal","text":"In the First Judges Case (S.P. Gupta v. Union of India, 1981), the Supreme Court held that ‘consultation’ does not mean ‘concurrence,’ and the executive had primacy in judicial appointments. In the Se"}]},{"id":"sec_171","title":"14.2 Qualifications of Judges","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"To be appointed as a judge of the Supreme Court, a person must: (a) be a citizen of India; (b) have been a judge of a High Court (or of two or more such courts in succession) for at least five years; "}]},{"id":"sec_172","title":"14.3 Jurisdiction of the Supreme Court","level":2,"paras":[]},{"id":"sub_173","title":"14.3.1 Original Jurisdiction (Article 131)","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Supreme Court has exclusive original jurisdiction in disputes between: (a) the Government of India and one or more States; (b) the Government of India and one or more States on one side and one or"}]},{"id":"sub_174","title":"14.3.2 Writ Jurisdiction (Article 32)","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Supreme Court can issue writs (habeas corpus, mandamus, prohibition, certiorari, and quo warranto) for the enforcement of Fundamental Rights. This jurisdiction is a Fundamental Right in itself."}]},{"id":"sub_175","title":"14.3.3 Appellate Jurisdiction (Articles 132–136)","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Supreme Court is the highest court of appeal. It hears appeals from High Courts in constitutional matters (Article 132), civil matters (Article 133), criminal matters (Article 134), and by special"}]},{"id":"sub_176","title":"14.3.4 Advisory Jurisdiction (Article 143)","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The President may refer any question of law or fact of public importance to the Supreme Court for its opinion. The Supreme Court may, after hearing, report to the President its opinion on the matter. "}]},{"id":"sub_177","title":"14.3.5 Court of Record (Article 129)","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Supreme Court is a Court of Record. Its judgments, proceedings, and acts are recorded for perpetual memory and testimony. These records are admitted as evidence and cannot be questioned in any cou"}]},{"id":"sec_178","title":"14.4 Judicial Review","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Judicial review is the power of the Supreme Court (and High Courts) to examine the constitutionality of legislative enactments and executive orders, and to declare them void if they are found to viola"}]},{"id":"sec_179","title":"14.5 Judicial Activism and Public Interest Litigation","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Judicial activism refers to the proactive role played by the judiciary in protecting the rights of citizens and filling gaps left by the legislature and executive. Public Interest Litigation (PIL), in"}]},{"id":"ch_180","title":"CHAPTER 15","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_181","title":"The High Courts","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_182","title":"15.1 Composition and Jurisdiction","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Each state has a High Court, and some High Courts have jurisdiction over more than one state or union territory (Article 214–231). The High Court consists of a Chief Justice and other judges appointed"}]},{"id":"sec_183","title":"15.2 Article 226 vs Article 32","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The writ jurisdiction of the High Courts under Article 226 is wider than that of the Supreme Court under Article 32. While Article 32 allows writs only for the enforcement of Fundamental Rights, Artic"},{"type":"normal","text":"PART XII"},{"type":"normal","text":"THE FEDERAL SYSTEM AND CENTRE-STATE RELATIONS"}]},{"id":"ch_184","title":"CHAPTER 16","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_185","title":"Centre-State Relations","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_186","title":"16.1 Legislative Relations (Articles 245–255)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The distribution of legislative powers between the Centre and the States is governed by Articles 245–255 and the Seventh Schedule. The Seventh Schedule contains three lists: Union List (List I – 97 su"},{"type":"normal","text":"Parliament can also legislate on State List subjects in certain circumstances: during a National Emergency (Article 250); when Rajya Sabha passes a resolution by a two-thirds majority that it is neces"}]},{"id":"sec_187","title":"16.2 Administrative Relations (Articles 256–263)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The executive power of the State is to be exercised in compliance with the laws made by Parliament (Article 256). The Centre can give directions to the States for the protection of railways, means of "}]},{"id":"sec_188","title":"16.3 Financial Relations (Articles 268–293)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Constitution provides for a detailed scheme of fiscal federalism. The Centre imposes and collects certain taxes and retains the revenue (e.g., customs duties, corporation tax). Some taxes are impo"}]},{"id":"sec_189","title":"16.4 Important Commissions on Centre-State Relations","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Sarkaria Commission (1983–1987, chaired by Justice R.S. Sarkaria) examined Centre-State relations and recommended several reforms, including the establishment of the Inter-State Council, restraint"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: Three Lists of the Seventh Schedule"},{"type":"normal","text":"PART XIII"},{"type":"normal","text":"EMERGENCY PROVISIONS"}]},{"id":"ch_190","title":"CHAPTER 17","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_191","title":"Emergency Provisions (Articles 352–360)","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_192","title":"17.1 National Emergency (Article 352)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The President can proclaim a National Emergency if he is satisfied that the security of India or any part thereof is threatened by war, external aggression, or armed rebellion. The 44th Amendment (197"},{"type":"normal","text":"Effects of National Emergency: The Centre’s executive power extends to directing any State on any matter. Parliament can legislate on State List subjects. The President can modify the distribution of "},{"type":"normal","text":"National Emergency has been proclaimed three times in India: in 1962 (Chinese aggression), 1971 (war with Pakistan), and 1975–1977 (Internal Emergency proclaimed by Indira Gandhi on grounds of ‘intern"}]},{"id":"sec_193","title":"17.2 President’s Rule / State Emergency (Article 356)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The President can impose President’s Rule in a State if, on the basis of a report from the Governor or otherwise, he is satisfied that the governance of the State cannot be carried on in accordance wi"}]},{"id":"sec_194","title":"17.3 Financial Emergency (Article 360)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The President can proclaim a Financial Emergency if he is satisfied that the financial stability or credit of India or any part thereof is threatened. The proclamation must be approved by both Houses "},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: Three Types of Emergency"},{"type":"normal","text":"PART XIV"},{"type":"normal","text":"STATE GOVERNMENT"}]},{"id":"ch_195","title":"CHAPTER 18","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_196","title":"The State Executive and Legislature","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_197","title":"18.1 The Governor (Articles 153–167)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Governor is the constitutional head of the State, appointed by the President (not elected). He holds office during the pleasure of the President (no fixed term, though by convention, the term is f"},{"type":"normal","text":"The Governor exercises discretionary powers in certain situations: recommending President’s Rule under Article 356; reserving a bill for the President’s consideration; appointing the Chief Minister wh"}]},{"id":"sec_198","title":"18.2 The Chief Minister and Council of Ministers","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Chief Minister is the real executive head of the State. He is appointed by the Governor (the leader of the majority party in the Legislative Assembly). The Chief Minister advises the Governor on t"}]},{"id":"sec_199","title":"18.3 State Legislature","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The State Legislature may be unicameral (Legislative Assembly only, called Vidhan Sabha) or bicameral (Legislative Assembly + Legislative Council, called Vidhan Parishad). Currently, only six states h"},{"type":"normal","text":"PART XV"},{"type":"normal","text":"LOCAL SELF-GOVERNMENT"}]},{"id":"ch_200","title":"CHAPTER 19","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_201","title":"Panchayati Raj and Municipalities","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_202","title":"19.1 Panchayati Raj (73rd Amendment Act, 1992)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The 73rd Constitutional Amendment Act of 1992, which came into effect on 24 April 1993, constitutionalised the Panchayati Raj system by adding Part IX (Articles 243–243O) and the Eleventh Schedule to "},{"type":"normal","text":"A State Finance Commission (Article 243-I) is to be constituted every five years to review the financial position of Panchayats and make recommendations regarding the distribution of taxes between the"}]},{"id":"sec_203","title":"19.2 Municipalities (74th Amendment Act, 1992)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The 74th Constitutional Amendment Act of 1992 constitutionalised urban local governance by adding Part IXA (Articles 243P–243ZG) and the Twelfth Schedule to the Constitution. The Twelfth Schedule cont"},{"type":"normal","text":"PART XVI"},{"type":"normal","text":"CONSTITUTIONAL BODIES"}]},{"id":"ch_204","title":"CHAPTER 20","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_205","title":"Election Commission, UPSC, Finance Commission, and CAG","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_206","title":"20.1 Election Commission of India (Article 324)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Election Commission of India (ECI) is a permanent constitutional body responsible for superintending, directing, and controlling the preparation of electoral rolls and the conduct of elections to "},{"type":"normal","text":"Following the Supreme Court’s direction in Anoop Baranwal v. Union of India (2023), a selection committee was mandated for the appointment of Election Commissioners. Parliament subsequently passed the"}]},{"id":"sec_207","title":"20.2 Union Public Service Commission (Articles 315–323)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The UPSC is a constitutional body that conducts examinations for appointment to the services of the Union (including the Civil Services Examination, Engineering Services, Medical Services, etc.). It c"}]},{"id":"sec_208","title":"20.3 Finance Commission (Article 280)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Finance Commission is constituted by the President every five years (or earlier) to make recommendations regarding the distribution of the net proceeds of taxes between the Centre and the States a"}]},{"id":"sec_209","title":"20.4 Comptroller and Auditor General of India (Articles 148–151)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Comptroller and Auditor General (CAG) of India is the guardian of the public purse and the supreme audit authority of India. He is appointed by the President and can be removed only through the sa"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: Constitutional Bodies at a Glance"},{"type":"normal","text":"PART XVII"},{"type":"normal","text":"NON-CONSTITUTIONAL AND STATUTORY BODIES"}]},{"id":"ch_210","title":"CHAPTER 21","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_211","title":"Important Non-Constitutional Bodies","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_212","title":"21.1 NITI Aayog","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The National Institution for Transforming India (NITI Aayog) was established on 1 January 2015 as a replacement for the Planning Commission (which was established in 1950 by an executive resolution of"}]},{"id":"sec_213","title":"21.2 National Human Rights Commission (NHRC)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The NHRC was established in 1993 under the Protection of Human Rights Act, 1993 (amended in 2006 and 2019). It is a statutory body (not constitutional). It consists of a Chairperson (who must be a ret"}]},{"id":"sec_214","title":"21.3 Central Bureau of Investigation (CBI)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The CBI was established in 1963 by a resolution of the Ministry of Home Affairs. It derives its power from the Delhi Special Police Establishment Act, 1946 (DSPE Act). The CBI is NOT a constitutional "}]},{"id":"sec_215","title":"21.4 Central Vigilance Commission (CVC)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The CVC was established in 1964 by an executive resolution. It was given statutory status by the Central Vigilance Commission Act, 2003. It consists of a Central Vigilance Commissioner (Chairperson) a"}]},{"id":"sec_216","title":"21.5 National Commission for Scheduled Castes (Article 338)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The National Commission for Scheduled Castes was established under Article 338 (as amended by the 89th Amendment, 2003). Earlier, there was a combined National Commission for Scheduled Castes and Sche"}]},{"id":"sec_217","title":"21.6 Lokpal and Lokayukta","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The concept of Lokpal (at the Centre) and Lokayukta (at the State level) was first recommended by the First Administrative Reforms Commission (1966–70, headed by Morarji Desai). The Lokpal and Lokayuk"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: Constitutional vs Non-Constitutional Bodies"},{"type":"normal","text":"PART XVIII"},{"type":"normal","text":"IMPORTANT CONSTITUTIONAL AMENDMENTS"}]},{"id":"ch_218","title":"CHAPTER 22","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_219","title":"Key Constitutional Amendments","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_220","title":"22.1 Major Amendments and Their Significance","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Indian Constitution has been amended over 100 times since its adoption in 1949. Some amendments have been minor and technical, while others have been transformative. The following are the most imp"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: Landmark Constitutional Amendments"},{"type":"normal","text":"PART XIX"},{"type":"normal","text":"LANDMARK SUPREME COURT CASES FOR UPSC PRELIMS"}]},{"id":"ch_221","title":"CHAPTER 23","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_222","title":"Essential Case Law","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_223","title":"23.1 Cases on Fundamental Rights and Basic Structure","level":2,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_224","title":"23.2 Cases on Article 21 and Personal Liberty","level":2,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_225","title":"23.3 Cases on Secularism and Federal Structure","level":2,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_226","title":"23.4 Other Important Cases","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"PART XX"},{"type":"normal","text":"GOVERNANCE, TRANSPARENCY, AND ACCOUNTABILITY"}]},{"id":"ch_227","title":"CHAPTER 24","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_228","title":"Governance and Public Policy","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_229","title":"24.1 Right to Information Act, 2005","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Right to Information (RTI) Act, 2005, enacted under Article 19(1)(a), provides a practical framework for citizens to access information held by public authorities. Every public authority is requir"}]},{"id":"sec_230","title":"24.2 Citizens’ Charter","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"A Citizens’ Charter is a document that outlines the commitment of a public service organisation to the citizens in respect of the services it provides. It sets out the standards of service, time limit"}]},{"id":"sec_231","title":"24.3 E-Governance","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"E-governance refers to the use of information and communication technology (ICT) to provide government services, exchange information, and facilitate transactions with citizens, businesses, and other "}]},{"id":"sec_232","title":"24.4 Self-Help Groups and Civil Society","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Self-Help Groups (SHGs) are small voluntary associations of people, usually from similar socio-economic backgrounds, who come together to solve common problems. SHGs typically have 10–20 members and p"}]},{"id":"sec_233","title":"24.5 Pressure Groups and Social Movements","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Pressure groups are organisations that seek to influence government policy without directly contesting elections. Types include: business groups (FICCI, CII, ASSOCHAM), trade unions (INTUC, AITUC, BMS"},{"type":"normal","text":"PART FINAL"},{"type":"normal","text":"COMPREHENSIVE REVISION"}]},{"id":"ch_234","title":"CHAPTER 25","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_235","title":"500 Key Prelims Facts","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_236","title":"Historical Background Facts (1–60)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"1. Regulating Act 1773 – First step by British Parliament to regulate the Company. 2. First Governor-General of Bengal – Warren Hastings (1773). 3. Supreme Court at Calcutta – established in 1774. 4. "},{"type":"normal","text":"21. GoI Act 1935 – proposed All-India Federation (never materialised). 22. GoI Act 1935 – provincial autonomy. 23. GoI Act 1935 – Federal Court established (1937). 24. GoI Act 1935 – 321 sections, 10 "},{"type":"normal","text":"41. Drafting Committee Chairman – Dr. B.R. Ambedkar. 42. Drafting Committee had 7 members. 43. Constitution adopted – 26 November 1949 (Constitution Day). 44. Constitution came into effect – 26 Januar"}]},{"id":"sec_237","title":"Core Constitutional Concepts (61–200)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"61. Article 13 – laws inconsistent with FR are void. 62. Doctrine of Eclipse – pre-constitutional void law revives if FR amended. 63. Article 14 – equality before law + equal protection. 64. Article 1"},{"type":"normal","text":"81. Maneka Gandhi (1978) – procedure must be just, fair, and reasonable. 82. Right to Privacy – Fundamental Right under Art 21 (Puttaswamy, 2017). 83. Article 21A – Right to Education (86th Amendment,"},{"type":"normal","text":"101. 42nd Amendment – added Fundamental Duties (original 10). 102. 86th Amendment – added 11th duty (education of children). 103. Swaran Singh Committee – recommended Fundamental Duties. 104. Presiden"},{"type":"normal","text":"121. Parliament = President + Rajya Sabha + Lok Sabha (Art 79). 122. RS maximum strength – 250 (238 elected + 12 nominated). 123. RS is permanent body; 1/3 members retire every 2 years. 124. RS member"},{"type":"normal","text":"141. Art 131 – SC original jurisdiction (Centre-State, State-State disputes). 142. Art 143 – SC advisory jurisdiction (non-binding). 143. Judicial review – basic feature (Kesavananda, 1973). 144. PIL "},{"type":"normal","text":"161. 73rd Amendment – Panchayati Raj; Part IX; Eleventh Schedule (29 subjects). 162. 74th Amendment – Municipalities; Part IXA; Twelfth Schedule (18 functions). 163. 3 tiers of Panchayati Raj: Gram Pa"},{"type":"normal","text":"181. NCST – Art 338A (89th Amendment, 2003). 182. National Commission for OBCs – Art 338B (102nd Amendment, 2018). 183. 1st Amendment – Art 15(4), Ninth Schedule, restriction on free speech. 184. 7th "}]},{"id":"sec_238","title":"Additional Key Facts (201–500)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"201. Schedules in the Constitution – currently 12. 202. First Schedule – States and UTs. 203. Second Schedule – salaries of President, VP, Governors, SC/HC judges, CAG. 204. Third Schedule – forms of "},{"type":"normal","text":"217. Article 1 – India, that is Bharat, shall be a Union of States. 218. Article 2 – Parliament may admit new states. 219. Article 3 – Parliament may form new states, alter boundaries (simple majority"},{"type":"normal","text":"241. Article 161 – Governor’s pardoning power (no death sentence). 242. Article 200 – Governor’s assent to bills (can reserve for President). 243. Article 213 – Governor’s ordinance power. 244. Articl"},{"type":"normal","text":"261. Article 343 – Hindi in Devanagari as official language. 262. Article 352 – National Emergency. 263. Article 356 – President’s Rule. 264. Article 360 – Financial Emergency. 265. Article 368 – Amen"},{"type":"normal","text":"281. Censure motion differs from no-confidence motion – censure states reasons; no-confidence does not. 282. Speaker of Lok Sabha – elected by LS members. 283. Speaker’s vote – only casting vote in ca"},{"type":"normal","text":"301. Article 365 – effect of failure to comply with directions given by Union. 302. Article 243-I – State Finance Commission. 303. Article 243-K – State Election Commission. 304. Article 279A – GST Co"},{"type":"normal","text":"311. Proclamation of Emergency must be based on WRITTEN advice of Cabinet (44th Amendment). 312. Special majority = majority of total membership + 2/3 of members present and voting. 313. Simple majori"},{"type":"normal","text":"331. Consolidated Fund – Art 266(1); all government revenue and borrowings. 332. Money from Consolidated Fund withdrawn only with Parliament’s approval. 333. Charged expenditure – not voted upon by Pa"},{"type":"normal","text":"351. Representation of People Act, 1950 – deals with allocation of seats, delimitation, electoral rolls. 352. Representation of People Act, 1951 – deals with conduct of elections, election disputes, d"},{"type":"normal","text":"371. President can appoint Inter-State Council under Art 263. 372. PM is the Chairman of NITI Aayog. 373. Cabinet Secretariat – facilitates smooth transaction of business. 374. Cabinet Secretary – sen"},{"type":"normal","text":"381. Art 262 – adjudication of inter-state water disputes. 382. River Water Disputes – Parliament can bar SC jurisdiction (Inter-State Water Disputes Act, 1956). 383. Cauvery Water Disputes Tribunal, "},{"type":"normal","text":"401. Gram Sabha – assembly of all adult members of a village; foundation of Panchayati Raj. 402. District Planning Committee – Art 243ZD (74th Amendment). 403. Metropolitan Planning Committee – Art 24"},{"type":"normal","text":"421. Three new criminal laws replaced IPC, CrPC, and Evidence Act from 1 July 2024: Bharatiya Nyaya Sanhita (BNS), Bharatiya Nagarik Suraksha Sanhita (BNSS), Bharatiya Sakshya Adhiniyam (BSA). 422. Sp"},{"type":"normal","text":"441. Rajya Sabha special powers: Art 249 (resolution for Parliament to legislate on State List); Art 312 (creation of All-India Services). 442. Lok Sabha special powers: Money Bills; No-confidence mot"},{"type":"normal","text":"451. Public Interest Litigation: can be filed under Art 32 (SC) or Art 226 (HC). 452. Epistolary jurisdiction: PIL can be filed via letter/postcard (e.g., Sunil Batra v. Delhi Administration). 453. Cu"},{"type":"normal","text":"471. SC held Aadhaar mandatory only for government subsidies/schemes, not for bank accounts or school admissions (Puttaswamy II, 2018). 472. Electoral Bond Scheme struck down by SC (Association for De"},{"type":"normal","text":"481. Art 110 defines Money Bill; Speaker’s certification is final. 482. Art 117(1): Money Bill introduced only with President’s recommendation. 483. Art 117(3): Financial Bill Category I – contains Mo"}]},{"id":"sec_239","title":"FINAL NOTE","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"trap","text":"This comprehensive textbook has covered the entire UPSC Prelims Polity syllabus, from the Regulating Act of 1773 to the most recent constitutional developments. Each topic has been presented with detailed analysis, relevant constitutional articles, landmark Supreme Court judgments, UPSC Trap warning"},{"type":"normal","text":"Remember: In UPSC Prelims, it is not just knowledge but precision that matters. Pay close attention to specific articles, exact amendment numbers, and the fine distinctions between similar concepts. G"}]},{"id":"ch_240","title":"CHAPTER 26","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_241","title":"The Twelve Schedules of the Constitution","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_242","title":"26.1 First Schedule – States and Union Territories","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The First Schedule lists the States and Union Territories of India with their territorial extent. At the time of the adoption of the Constitution, India had Part A States (erstwhile British Indian pro"}]},{"id":"sec_243","title":"26.2 Second Schedule – Emoluments, Allowances, Privileges","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Second Schedule contains provisions relating to emoluments, allowances, privileges, and other conditions of service of the President of India (Part A), the Governors of States (Part B), the Speake"}]},{"id":"sec_244","title":"26.3 Third Schedule – Forms of Oaths and Affirmations","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Third Schedule contains the forms of oaths and affirmations to be taken by various constitutional functionaries, including the President, the Vice President, Ministers, Members of Parliament, Memb"}]},{"id":"sec_245","title":"26.4 Fourth Schedule – Allocation of Rajya Sabha Seats","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Fourth Schedule specifies the allocation of seats in the Rajya Sabha to the States and Union Territories. The allocation is broadly in proportion to the population of each State, though smaller st"}]},{"id":"sec_246","title":"26.5 Fifth Schedule – Scheduled Areas and Scheduled Tribes","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Fifth Schedule contains provisions for the administration and control of Scheduled Areas and Scheduled Tribes in any state other than the states of Assam, Meghalaya, Tripura, and Mizoram (which ar"}]},{"id":"sec_247","title":"26.6 Sixth Schedule – Administration of Tribal Areas in NE","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Sixth Schedule contains provisions for the administration of tribal areas in the states of Assam, Meghalaya, Tripura, and Mizoram. It provides for the creation of Autonomous District Councils and "}]},{"id":"sec_248","title":"26.7 Seventh Schedule – Division of Subjects","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Seventh Schedule contains the three legislative lists – Union List, State List, and Concurrent List – which divide legislative competence between the Union and the States. This has been discussed "}]},{"id":"sec_249","title":"26.8 Eighth Schedule – Official Languages","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Eighth Schedule lists the official languages recognized by the Constitution. Originally, 14 languages were included: Assamese, Bengali, Gujarati, Hindi, Kannada, Kashmiri, Malayalam, Marathi, Oriy"}]},{"id":"sec_250","title":"26.9 Ninth Schedule","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Ninth Schedule was added by the 1st Amendment Act of 1951. It contains a list of laws that are protected from judicial review on the ground of violation of Fundamental Rights. Originally, it conta"}]},{"id":"sec_251","title":"26.10 Tenth Schedule – Anti-Defection Law","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Tenth Schedule was added by the 52nd Amendment Act of 1985. It contains provisions to disqualify members of Parliament and State Legislatures on grounds of defection. A member is deemed to have de"}]},{"id":"sec_252","title":"26.11 Eleventh and Twelfth Schedules","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Eleventh Schedule, added by the 73rd Amendment (1992), lists 29 functional items of Panchayats including agriculture, land improvement, minor irrigation, fisheries, animal husbandry, social forest"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: All 12 Schedules"}]},{"id":"ch_253","title":"CHAPTER 27","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_254","title":"Miscellaneous Important Articles","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_255","title":"27.1 Article 1 – Name and Territory of the Union","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Article 1 states: ‘India, that is Bharat, shall be a Union of States.’ The use of the word ‘Union’ instead of ‘Federation’ was deliberate. Dr. B.R. Ambedkar explained that the word ‘Union’ was preferr"}]},{"id":"sec_256","title":"27.2 Articles 2 and 3 – Admission and Formation of New States","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Article 2 empowers Parliament to admit new states into the Union of India or to establish new states on such terms and conditions as it thinks fit. Article 3 empowers Parliament to form new states by "}]},{"id":"sec_257","title":"27.3 Special Provisions for Certain States (Articles 371–371J)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Constitution contains special provisions for certain states to address their unique historical, cultural, or geographical circumstances. Article 371 provides special provisions for Maharashtra and"}]},{"id":"sec_258","title":"27.4 Official Language (Articles 343–351)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Part XVII of the Constitution (Articles 343–351) deals with the official language. Article 343 declares Hindi in Devanagari script as the official language of the Union. However, Article 343(2) provid"}]},{"id":"ch_259","title":"CHAPTER 28","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_260","title":"200 MCQ Traps for UPSC Prelims","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_261","title":"28.1 Traps on Historical Background (1–30)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"1. Governor-General of Bengal (Regulating Act 1773) is NOT the same as Governor-General of India (Charter Act 1833). 2. Supreme Court at Calcutta (1774) applied English law, NOT Indian law. 3. Pitt’s "},{"type":"normal","text":"16. GoI Act 1935 continued as the governing law even after 15 August 1947 until 26 January 1950. 17. Lord Mountbatten was the FIRST Governor-General of independent India, not the LAST Viceroy (he was "}]},{"id":"sec_262","title":"28.2 Traps on Constitution-Making (31–50)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"31. Constituent Assembly was NOT directly elected – it was indirectly elected by provincial legislatures. 32. M.N. Roy proposed the IDEA of CA (1934); INC demanded it in 1935. 33. Membership: 389 orig"}]},{"id":"sec_263","title":"28.3 Traps on Fundamental Rights and DPSPs (51–100)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"51. Article 14 is available to ALL persons (citizens + foreigners). 52. Article 19 is available ONLY to citizens. 53. Article 15 discrimination is on ‘grounds ONLY of’ (single ground is enough; but if"},{"type":"normal","text":"61. Article 20 and 21 CANNOT be suspended even during Emergency (44th Amendment). 62. Article 21 says ‘procedure established by law,’ not ‘due process’ – but Maneka Gandhi (1978) effectively read in d"},{"type":"normal","text":"71. Article 26 is for RELIGIOUS DENOMINATIONS (not just minorities). 72. Article 27 prohibits tax for promotion of ANY religion (not just a specific one). 73. Article 28 prohibits religious instructio"},{"type":"normal","text":"81. Article 37 says DPSPs are fundamental in GOVERNANCE but NOT justiciable. 82. Article 38 was amended by the 44th Amendment (added minimisation of inequalities). 83. Article 39A (free legal aid) was"},{"type":"normal","text":"91. 11th Fundamental Duty (education of children 6–14) was added by 86th Amendment, not 42nd. 92. Swaran Singh Committee recommended Fundamental Duties; Verma Committee recommended their operationalis"}]},{"id":"sec_264","title":"28.4 Traps on Union Executive and Parliament (101–150)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"101. President’s electoral college: Elected MPs + Elected MLAs only (NO nominated members, NO MLC members). 102. VP’s electoral college: ALL MPs (elected + nominated) of BOTH Houses (NO MLAs). 103. Pr"},{"type":"normal","text":"111. Ordinance valid for 6 weeks after Parliament reassembles (not 6 months). 112. Maximum ordinance validity: 6 months + 6 weeks. 113. Re-promulgation without legislative approval is unconstitutional"},{"type":"normal","text":"121. Lok Sabha term: 5 years (not 6; it was temporarily 6 years under 42nd Amendment, restored by 44th). 122. RS member term: 6 years; 1/3 retire every 2 years. 123. Quorum in Parliament: 1/10 of tota"},{"type":"normal","text":"131. Question Hour: first hour; Starred (oral answer) and Unstarred (written answer). 132. Zero Hour: starts at 12 noon; not in Rules of Procedure (informal device). 133. Calling Attention Motion: uni"},{"type":"normal","text":"141. Casting vote: Speaker votes only to break a tie. 142. Deputy Speaker: elected by LS members; not from opposition (unlike PAC Chairman). 143. Leader of Opposition: statutory recognition under 1977"}]},{"id":"sec_265","title":"28.5 Traps on Judiciary and Emergency (151–200)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"151. SC retirement age: 65; HC retirement age: 62. 152. Collegium system is judicial creation (not constitutional or statutory). 153. NJAC (99th Amendment) was STRUCK DOWN; Collegium continues. 154. A"},{"type":"normal","text":"161. National Emergency (Art 352): war, external aggression, or ARMED REBELLION (not ‘internal disturbance’). 162. ‘Internal disturbance’ was replaced by ‘armed rebellion’ by 44th Amendment. 163. Writ"},{"type":"normal","text":"171. Governor CANNOT pardon death sentence (only President can). 172. Governor’s ordinance power: Art 213 (state level); President’s ordinance power: Art 123 (central level). 173. Only 6 states have b"},{"type":"normal","text":"181. CEC removal: only by impeachment. Other ECs: by President on CEC’s recommendation. 182. UPSC Chairman: 6 years or age 65; NOT eligible for further government employment. 183. Finance Commission i"},{"type":"normal","text":"191. 42nd Amendment is called ‘Mini Constitution’ for the extent of changes. 192. 44th Amendment reversed many 42nd Amendment provisions. 193. Anti-defection law: 52nd Amendment (1985), not 42nd or 44"}]},{"id":"ch_266","title":"CHAPTER 29","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_267","title":"50 Comprehensive Revision Tables","level":1,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: 1. Governor-Generals and Viceroys"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: 2. Key Constitutional Articles"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: 3. Minimum Ages for Various Posts"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: 4. Retirement Ages"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: 5. Types of Majorities"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: 6. Parts of the Constitution"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: 7. Borrowed Features Summary"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: 8. National Emergencies Proclaimed"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: 9. Tenth Schedule (Anti-Defection) Key Points"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: 10. Key Landmark Cases Quick Reference"}]},{"id":"ch_268","title":"CHAPTER 30","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_269","title":"Parliamentary Procedures and Devices in Detail","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_270","title":"30.1 The Budget Process","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Annual Financial Statement, commonly known as the Budget, is laid before both Houses of Parliament by the President under Article 112. Since 2017, the Budget is presented on 1 February (previously"},{"type":"normal","text":"The Budget goes through several stages. First, the Finance Minister presents the Budget in the Lok Sabha (the Budget is only ‘laid’ before the Rajya Sabha, which has no power to vote on it). Second, a"},{"type":"normal","text":"Cut Motions are devices available to members during the discussion on Demands for Grants. There are three types: the Disapproval of Policy Cut (the amount of the demand be reduced to Re 1, implying di"},{"type":"normal","text":"The concept of ‘Vote on Account’ is used when the Budget is unlikely to be passed before the commencement of the new financial year (1 April). A Vote on Account allows the government to draw from the "}]},{"id":"sec_271","title":"30.2 Types of Parliamentary Motions","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"A motion is a formal proposal made by a member to the House for the purpose of eliciting a decision. There are several categories of motions in Parliament:"},{"type":"normal","text":"No-Confidence Motion (Article 75): A motion expressing the House’s lack of confidence in the Council of Ministers. It can be moved in the Lok Sabha only. It needs the support of at least 50 members to"},{"type":"normal","text":"Censure Motion: Unlike a no-confidence motion, a censure motion must state the specific reasons for censure. It can be moved against the entire Council of Ministers or against specific ministers. If i"},{"type":"normal","text":"Adjournment Motion: This is a motion to adjourn the regular business of the House to discuss a matter of urgent public importance. It can be moved only in the Lok Sabha. It requires the leave of the S"},{"type":"normal","text":"Calling Attention Motion: This is a device unique to Indian parliamentary procedure, not found in the British Parliament. Any member may, with the prior permission of the Speaker, call the attention o"},{"type":"normal","text":"Short Duration Discussion (Two-Hour Discussion): Any member may raise a discussion on a matter of urgent public importance. The discussion must not exceed two hours, and no formal motion is moved or v"},{"type":"normal","text":"Half-an-Hour Discussion: This is held on a matter of sufficient public importance arising out of an answer given to a question during Question Hour. It is held three times a week (Monday, Wednesday, a"},{"type":"normal","text":"Point of Order: A member may raise a point of order to draw the attention of the Chair to a violation of the rules of procedure. The Speaker’s ruling on a point of order is final."}]},{"id":"sec_272","title":"30.3 Parliamentary Privileges in Detail","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Parliamentary privileges are special rights, immunities, and exemptions enjoyed by each House of Parliament, its committees, and its members. They are essential for the independent functioning of the "},{"type":"normal","text":"Individual privileges include: freedom of speech in Parliament (no member is liable to any proceedings in any court for anything said or any vote given in Parliament or its committees – this is an abs"},{"type":"normal","text":"Collective privileges include: the right to publish reports, debates, and proceedings, and the right to prohibit others from publishing the same; the right to exclude strangers from the proceedings; t"},{"type":"normal","text":"Unlike the UK, where parliamentary privileges are codified (Parliamentary Privileges Act, 1770, and others), Indian parliamentary privileges are not comprehensively codified. Article 105(3) provides t"}]},{"id":"ch_273","title":"CHAPTER 31","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_274","title":"The Electoral System in Detail","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_275","title":"31.1 The Election Commission of India","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Election Commission of India (ECI) is one of the few constitutional bodies that has enjoyed a consistently high reputation for integrity and independence. Article 324 vests the superintendence, di"},{"type":"normal","text":"The Chief Election Commissioner enjoys the same security of tenure as a Supreme Court judge – he can be removed only through a process of impeachment (by an address of Parliament supported by a specia"}]},{"id":"sec_276","title":"31.2 Electoral Systems Used in India","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"India uses two different electoral systems for different types of elections. The First-Past-the-Post (FPTP) system is used for elections to the Lok Sabha and State Legislative Assemblies. Under this s"},{"type":"normal","text":"The system of Proportional Representation with Single Transferable Vote (PR-STV) is used for elections to the Rajya Sabha, State Legislative Councils, and the offices of President and Vice President. "}]},{"id":"sec_277","title":"31.3 Anti-Defection Law in Practice","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Tenth Schedule (Anti-Defection Law) was added to the Constitution by the 52nd Amendment Act of 1985 to combat the ‘Aaya Ram Gaya Ram’ phenomenon of frequent party-switching by legislators, which h"},{"type":"normal","text":"Under the Tenth Schedule, a member of a House belonging to a political party is deemed to have defected if he voluntarily gives up his membership of that party, or if he votes or abstains from voting "},{"type":"normal","text":"The original Tenth Schedule contained a provision for ‘split,’ which allowed a group of not less than one-third of the members of a legislative party to form a separate group without being disqualifie"}]},{"id":"sec_278","title":"31.4 Representation of the People Acts","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Representation of the People Act, 1950, deals with the allocation of seats in the Lok Sabha and State Legislative Assemblies, the delimitation of constituencies, the preparation and revision of el"}]},{"id":"ch_279","title":"CHAPTER 32","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_280","title":"Special Constitutional Topics","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_281","title":"32.1 The Doctrine of Basic Structure","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Basic Structure Doctrine is the most significant judicial creation in Indian constitutional law. It was established in Kesavananda Bharati v. State of Kerala (1973), where a 13-judge Constitution "},{"type":"normal","text":"The Supreme Court has not provided an exhaustive list of what constitutes the basic structure. Instead, it has identified various features as part of the basic structure through a series of cases. In "},{"type":"normal","text":"The doctrine has been applied to strike down several constitutional amendments, including: Section 4 of the 42nd Amendment (which gave Parliament unlimited amending power – struck down in Minerva Mill"}]},{"id":"sec_282","title":"32.2 Centre-State Relations: Detailed Analysis","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Indian federal system is characterised by a strong Centre and relatively weaker States. This centralised federalism was a deliberate choice by the Constitution-makers, influenced by the traumatic "},{"type":"normal","text":"The legislative relations are governed by Articles 245–255 and the Seventh Schedule. Article 245 provides that Parliament may make laws for the whole or any part of the territory of India, and the Sta"},{"type":"normal","text":"The administrative relations are governed by Articles 256–263. Article 256 requires the executive power of every State to be exercised in compliance with Union laws. Article 257 allows the Centre to g"},{"type":"normal","text":"The financial relations are governed by Articles 264–293. The Constitution provides for a detailed scheme of fiscal federalism. Taxes are divided into several categories: taxes levied by the Union and"}]},{"id":"sec_283","title":"32.3 The Governor Controversy","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The role of the Governor has been one of the most contentious issues in Indian federalism. Critics argue that Governors are often used by the Centre as agents to destabilise or influence state governm"},{"type":"normal","text":"The Sarkaria Commission (1988) recommended that Governors should be eminent persons from outside the State, should not be active politicians, should be appointed after consultation with the Chief Mini"}]},{"id":"sec_284","title":"32.4 Cooperative and Competitive Federalism","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Indian federal system has evolved from a centralised model to one that increasingly emphasises cooperative federalism – a collaborative approach where the Centre and States work together as partne"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: Important Commissions on Centre-State Relations"}]},{"id":"ch_285","title":"CHAPTER 33","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_286","title":"The Amendment Procedure in Detail (Article 368)","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_287","title":"33.1 Three Categories of Amendments","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Constitution provides for three categories of amendments, each requiring a different level of consensus:"},{"type":"normal","text":"Category 1 – Simple Majority: Certain provisions can be changed by Parliament by a simple majority (more than 50% of members present and voting). These changes are NOT considered amendments under Arti"},{"type":"normal","text":"Category 2 – Special Majority of Parliament: Most provisions of the Constitution can be amended by a special majority of Parliament, which means: (a) a majority of the total membership of each House ("},{"type":"normal","text":"Category 3 – Special Majority + State Ratification: Certain provisions that affect the federal structure require, in addition to the special majority, ratification by the legislatures of at least half"}]},{"id":"sec_288","title":"33.2 The Process of Amendment","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"A Constitutional Amendment Bill can be introduced in either House of Parliament. It can be introduced by a minister or by a private member. It does NOT require the prior recommendation of the Presiden"}]},{"id":"ch_289","title":"CHAPTER 34","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_290","title":"Union Territories – Governance and Special Provisions","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_291","title":"34.1 Constitutional Provisions","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Union Territories are dealt with in Part VIII of the Constitution (Articles 239–241). Unlike States, which have their own elected governments and legislatures, Union Territories are administered by th"},{"type":"normal","text":"The National Capital Territory of Delhi has a special status under Article 239AA (inserted by the 69th Amendment, 1991). Delhi has a Legislative Assembly and a Council of Ministers headed by a Chief M"},{"type":"normal","text":"Puducherry also has an elected legislature and Council of Ministers under the Government of Union Territories Act, 1963. The Administrator of Puducherry (Lieutenant Governor) exercises powers similar "},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: Union Territories of India (2024)"}]},{"id":"ch_292","title":"CHAPTER 35","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_293","title":"Detailed Analysis of Articles 14–35: Case-by-Case","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_294","title":"35.1 Article 14 – The Evolving Doctrine of Equality","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Article 14 of the Constitution provides that ‘The State shall not deny to any person equality before the law or the equal protection of the laws within the territory of India.’ This provision has been"},{"type":"normal","text":"However, in E.P. Royappa v. State of Tamil Nadu (1974), Justice P.N. Bhagwati introduced the ‘new doctrine of equality’ or the ‘arbitrariness test.’ He held that equality is a dynamic concept and that"},{"type":"normal","text":"In Shayara Bano v. Union of India (2017), the Supreme Court invoked Article 14 (among other provisions) to strike down the practice of triple talaq (talaq-e-biddat) as arbitrary and violative of the f"},{"type":"normal","text":"In State of West Bengal v. Anwar Ali Sarkar (1952), the Supreme Court laid down that a law providing for a different procedure for trial of certain offences without laying down any guiding principle f"}]},{"id":"sec_295","title":"35.2 Article 15 – Discrimination and Affirmative Action","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Article 15 has been progressively expanded through amendments to enable the State to take affirmative action for disadvantaged groups while maintaining the principle of non-discrimination. The origina"},{"type":"normal","text":"The pivotal expansion came with Article 15(4), added by the 1st Amendment Act of 1951. This was a direct response to the Supreme Court’s decision in State of Madras v. Champakam Dorairajan (1951), whe"},{"type":"normal","text":"Article 15(5), added by the 93rd Amendment Act of 2005, specifically allows the State to make special provisions for the advancement of socially and educationally backward classes, Scheduled Castes, a"},{"type":"normal","text":"Most recently, Article 15(6), added by the 103rd Amendment Act of 2019, allows the State to make special provisions for the advancement of any economically weaker sections of citizens (other than SC/S"}]},{"id":"sec_296","title":"35.3 Article 19 – Freedom of Speech and Its Reasonable Restrictions","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Article 19(1)(a) guarantees to all citizens the freedom of speech and expression. This is one of the most important and frequently litigated provisions of the Constitution. The scope of this freedom h"},{"type":"normal","text":"Article 19(2) permits the State to impose ‘reasonable restrictions’ on the freedom of speech and expression in the interests of: the sovereignty and integrity of India, the security of the State, frie"},{"type":"normal","text":"Several important cases have defined the boundaries of free speech. In Shreya Singhal v. Union of India (2015), the Supreme Court struck down Section 66A of the Information Technology Act, 2000 (which"}]},{"id":"sec_297","title":"35.4 Article 21 – The Most Dynamic Right","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Article 21 has been described as the ‘residuary fundamental right’ because of its expansive interpretation over the decades. Starting from a narrow interpretation in A.K. Gopalan (1950), the Supreme C"},{"type":"normal","text":"Right to live with human dignity (Francis Coralie Mullin v. Administrator, Union Territory of Delhi, 1981); Right to livelihood (Olga Tellis v. Bombay Municipal Corporation, 1985); Right to health and"},{"type":"normal","text":"The jurisprudence of Article 21 illustrates the Indian judiciary’s creative and purposive approach to constitutional interpretation, transforming a brief textual provision into a comprehensive charter"}]},{"id":"sec_298","title":"35.5 Article 32 – The Heart and Soul of the Constitution","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Dr. B.R. Ambedkar famously declared that Article 32 is the ‘most important’ article of the Constitution, without which the Constitution would be a ‘nullity.’ He called it the ‘heart and soul’ of the C"},{"type":"normal","text":"The significance of Article 32 is highlighted by the fact that it is itself a Fundamental Right. This means that a citizen can approach the Supreme Court directly for the enforcement of any Fundamenta"}]},{"id":"ch_299","title":"CHAPTER 36","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_300","title":"Accountability Mechanisms and Good Governance","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_301","title":"36.1 Right to Information and Transparency","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Right to Information Act, 2005, is one of the most significant governance reforms in post-independence India. The Act was the culmination of a long struggle for transparency, led primarily by the "},{"type":"normal","text":"The RTI Act, 2005, provides that every citizen has the right to request information from a ‘public authority,’ which is required to respond within 30 days (48 hours if the information concerns the lif"},{"type":"normal","text":"Section 8 of the RTI Act specifies the exemptions from disclosure. These include: information that would prejudicially affect the sovereignty and integrity of India, the security, strategic, scientifi"}]},{"id":"sec_302","title":"36.2 The Lokpal and Lokayuktas","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The concept of an anti-corruption ombudsman was first recommended by the First Administrative Reforms Commission (1966–70), headed by Morarji Desai. The ARC recommended the creation of Lokpal at the C"},{"type":"normal","text":"The India Against Corruption movement, led by Anna Hazare in 2011, created enormous public pressure for the passage of a strong Lokpal law. After prolonged debates, the Lokpal and Lokayuktas Act was f"},{"type":"normal","text":"The first Lokpal, Justice Pinaki Chandra Ghose (former Supreme Court judge), was appointed in March 2019 – more than five years after the Act was passed. This delay attracted significant criticism. Th"}]},{"id":"sec_303","title":"36.3 Accountability of the Executive","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Constitution provides several mechanisms for ensuring the accountability of the executive to the legislature and to the people. Collective Responsibility (Article 75(3)) means that the Council of "}]},{"id":"sec_304","title":"36.4 Decentralisation and Subsidiarity","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The principle of subsidiarity holds that matters should be handled by the smallest, lowest, or least centralised authority capable of addressing them effectively. The 73rd and 74th Amendments to the C"},{"type":"normal","text":"However, the implementation of decentralisation has been uneven across States. States like Kerala, West Bengal, Karnataka, and Rajasthan have made significant progress in devolution of functions, func"},{"type":"normal","text":"Key challenges in decentralisation include: the reluctance of state governments to part with power and resources; the inadequacy of State Finance Commissions (which are often not constituted on time o"}]},{"id":"ch_305","title":"CHAPTER 37","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_306","title":"Additional Revision Tables (11–50)","level":1,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: 11. Rights Available to Citizens Only vs All Persons"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: 12. Pardoning Powers: President vs Governor"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: 13. Lok Sabha vs Rajya Sabha – Key Differences"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: 14. Constitutional Bodies vs Statutory Bodies"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: 15. Types of Bills in Parliament"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: 16. Key Constitutional Definitions"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: 17. Joint Sittings Held So Far"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: 18. Important Doctrines in Constitutional Law"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: 19. First Holders of Important Offices"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: 20. Amendment Procedure: What Needs What?"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: 21. Comparison: National Emergency vs President’s Rule vs Financial Emergency"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: 22. 22 Languages in the Eighth Schedule"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: 23. Important Reports and Committees"}]},{"id":"ch_307","title":"CHAPTER 38","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_308","title":"Detailed Analysis of Landmark Supreme Court Judgments","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_309","title":"38.1 The Basic Structure Trilogy","level":2,"paras":[]},{"id":"sub_310","title":"38.1.1 Shankari Prasad v. Union of India (1951)","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"This was the first case to test the scope of Parliament’s amending power under Article 368. The petitioner challenged the validity of the 1st Amendment Act, 1951, which had added Article 15(4) and the"},{"type":"normal","text":"The significance of this case for UPSC is threefold: first, it established the distinction between ‘law’ under Article 13 and ‘amendment’ under Article 368; second, it upheld the validity of the 1st A"}]},{"id":"sub_311","title":"38.1.2 Golaknath v. State of Punjab (1967)","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"In this case, an eleven-judge bench of the Supreme Court, by a narrow 6:5 majority, reversed the Shankari Prasad position and held that Parliament CANNOT amend Fundamental Rights. Chief Justice Subba "},{"type":"normal","text":"The Golaknath decision sent shockwaves through the political establishment. If Parliament could not amend Fundamental Rights, then important social legislation (including land reforms and reservations"}]},{"id":"sub_312","title":"38.1.3 Kesavananda Bharati v. State of Kerala (1973)","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"This is the most significant case in Indian constitutional history. The case was heard by the largest-ever Constitution Bench of the Supreme Court – 13 judges – over 68 working days. The petitioner, S"},{"type":"normal","text":"By a narrow 7:6 majority, the Court held: (a) Parliament has the power to amend any provision of the Constitution, including Fundamental Rights (thus overruling Golaknath on this point); (b) the 24th "},{"type":"normal","text":"The specific features identified as part of the basic structure by the majority judges included (though different judges listed different features): supremacy of the Constitution, the republican and d"},{"type":"normal","text":"The significance of this case cannot be overstated. It established a permanent check on the amending power of Parliament, ensuring that no government, however large its majority, can subvert the funda"}]},{"id":"sec_313","title":"38.2 The Emergency Cases","level":2,"paras":[]},{"id":"sub_314","title":"38.2.1 Indira Nehru Gandhi v. Raj Narain (1975)","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"This case arose from the election petition filed by Raj Narain challenging Indira Gandhi’s election from the Rae Bareli constituency in the 1971 general elections. Justice Jagmohan Lal Sinha of the Al"}]},{"id":"sub_315","title":"38.2.2 ADM Jabalpur v. Shivkant Shukla (1976) – The Habeas Corpus Case","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"During the Internal Emergency (1975–77), the President issued an order under Article 359 suspending the enforcement of Articles 14, 21, and 22. Several detenues challenged their detention through habe"},{"type":"normal","text":"This case is widely regarded as the darkest moment in the history of the Indian Supreme Court. In K.S. Puttaswamy v. Union of India (2017), a nine-judge bench unanimously overruled the ADM Jabalpur de"}]},{"id":"sec_316","title":"38.3 Cases on Reservation","level":2,"paras":[]},{"id":"sub_317","title":"38.3.1 State of Madras v. Champakam Dorairajan (1951)","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"This was the first major case on reservations. The Madras Government had issued an order fixing the proportion of seats in educational institutions for different communities based on caste and religio"}]},{"id":"sub_318","title":"38.3.2 Indra Sawhney v. Union of India (1992) – The Mandal Case","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"This landmark nine-judge bench decision arose from the challenge to the Government of India’s decision to implement the Mandal Commission’s recommendation to provide 27% reservation in central governm"}]},{"id":"sub_319","title":"38.3.3 M. Nagaraj v. Union of India (2006)","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"This case challenged the constitutional amendments providing for reservation in promotions for SCs and STs (Articles 16(4A) and 16(4B)). The Supreme Court upheld the amendments as constitutionally val"}]},{"id":"sub_320","title":"38.3.4 Janhit Abhiyan v. Union of India (2022)","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"This five-judge bench decision upheld the constitutional validity of the 103rd Amendment Act, 2019, which provides for 10% reservation for Economically Weaker Sections (EWS) in educational institution"}]},{"id":"sec_321","title":"38.4 Cases on Personal Liberty and Privacy","level":2,"paras":[]},{"id":"sub_322","title":"38.4.1 K.S. Puttaswamy v. Union of India (2017)","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"This nine-judge bench decision unanimously held that the right to privacy is a constitutionally protected fundamental right under Article 21 of the Constitution. The case arose in the context of chall"}]},{"id":"sub_323","title":"38.4.2 Navtej Singh Johar v. Union of India (2018)","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"In this landmark case, a five-judge bench of the Supreme Court unanimously read down Section 377 of the Indian Penal Code (which criminalised ‘carnal intercourse against the order of nature’) insofar "}]},{"id":"sub_324","title":"38.4.3 Common Cause v. Union of India (2018) – Right to Die with Dignity","level":3,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"In this case, a five-judge bench of the Supreme Court recognised the right to die with dignity as a fundamental right under Article 21. The Court legalised passive euthanasia (withdrawing life support"}]},{"id":"ch_325","title":"CHAPTER 39","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_326","title":"All-India Services and Public Administration","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_327","title":"39.1 All-India Services (Article 312)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Article 312 provides for the creation of All-India Services common to both the Union and the States. These services are unique to the Indian federal system and serve as an integrating force, ensuring "},{"type":"normal","text":"Members of the All-India Services are recruited by the Centre (through the UPSC) but serve both the Centre and the States. They are allocated to State cadres upon recruitment and serve under the State"}]},{"id":"sec_328","title":"39.2 The UPSC and State PSCs (Articles 315–323)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Union Public Service Commission (UPSC) and the State Public Service Commissions are constitutional bodies established under Article 315. The UPSC conducts examinations for recruitment to the All-I"},{"type":"normal","text":"Article 317 provides for the removal of a Chairman or member of the UPSC or State PSC. They can be removed by the President (in case of the UPSC) or the Governor (in case of a State PSC) on the ground"}]},{"id":"sec_329","title":"39.3 Civil Services Reforms","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"India’s civil services system has been the subject of numerous reform proposals. The First Administrative Reforms Commission (1966–70, chaired by Morarji Desai and later by K. Hanumanthaiya) made wide"},{"type":"normal","text":"Recent reforms include: the introduction of the lateral entry scheme (recruiting domain experts from the private sector and academia into joint secretary-level positions in the Central Government); th"}]},{"id":"ch_330","title":"CHAPTER 40","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_331","title":"Constitutional Morality and Contemporary Governance Concepts","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_332","title":"40.1 Constitutional Morality","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The concept of constitutional morality, though not explicitly defined in the Constitution, has been invoked by the Supreme Court in several landmark cases. The term was first used by Dr. B.R. Ambedkar"},{"type":"normal","text":"The Supreme Court has invoked constitutional morality in several important cases. In Naz Foundation v. Government of NCT of Delhi (2009), the Delhi High Court used the concept of constitutional morali"},{"type":"normal","text":"Constitutional morality encompasses several principles: adherence to constitutional procedures and norms; respect for the rights of minorities and dissenters; separation of powers and checks and balan"}]},{"id":"sec_333","title":"40.2 Separation of Powers","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Indian Constitution does not expressly provide for the separation of powers as in the American Constitution (which explicitly vests legislative power in Congress, executive power in the President,"},{"type":"normal","text":"In practice, there is significant overlap between the three organs: the executive exercises legislative power through ordinances (Articles 123 and 213); the legislature exercises judicial functions th"}]},{"id":"sec_334","title":"40.3 Rule of Law","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The concept of the Rule of Law, derived from the British constitutional tradition (particularly from A.V. Dicey’s ‘Introduction to the Study of the Law of the Constitution,’ 1885), is fundamental to t"}]},{"id":"sec_335","title":"40.4 Welfare State","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Indian Constitution establishes India as a welfare state. While the Preamble declares the objectives of social, economic, and political justice, the Directive Principles of State Policy provide th"}]},{"id":"sec_336","title":"40.5 Secularism in the Indian Context","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Indian secularism differs fundamentally from Western secularism. While Western secularism (particularly the American model) emphasises a ‘wall of separation’ between religion and the State (the State "},{"type":"normal","text":"In S.R. Bommai v. Union of India (1994), the Supreme Court unequivocally held that secularism is a basic feature of the Constitution and cannot be altered even by a constitutional amendment. The Court"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: 24. Summary of Constitutional Morality Principles"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: 25. Summary: Article 21 Expanded Rights"}]},{"id":"ch_337","title":"CHAPTER 41","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_338","title":"Detailed Comparison: President and Governor","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_339","title":"41.1 Election, Appointment, and Removal","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The President of India is elected by an electoral college consisting of the elected members of both Houses of Parliament and the elected members of the Legislative Assemblies of all States and the Uni"},{"type":"normal","text":"The Governor of a State, in contrast, is NOT elected but is appointed by the President (i.e., the central government). Article 155 provides that the Governor shall be appointed by the President by war"}]},{"id":"sec_340","title":"41.2 Powers Compared","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Both the President and the Governor have executive, legislative, financial, and judicial powers, but there are important differences. In terms of executive power, the President appoints the Prime Mini"},{"type":"normal","text":"In terms of legislative power, both can summon, prorogue, and address their respective legislatures. Both have ordinance-making power (Articles 123 and 213 respectively). However, there is a critical "},{"type":"normal","text":"In terms of judicial power, the President has the power to grant pardons, reprieves, respites, or remissions of punishment under Article 72. This power extends to: (a) all cases where the punishment o"}]},{"id":"sec_341","title":"41.3 Discretionary Powers of the Governor","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Unlike the President, who is constitutionally bound to act on the advice of the Council of Ministers in virtually all matters (Article 74, as amended by the 42nd and 44th Amendments), the Governor has"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: 26. President vs Governor – Comprehensive Comparison"}]},{"id":"ch_342","title":"CHAPTER 42","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_343","title":"Panchayati Raj: Detailed Analysis","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_344","title":"42.1 Historical Evolution of Panchayati Raj","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The concept of village self-governance has deep roots in Indian history. Ancient texts like the Rig Veda, the Arthashastra (by Kautilya), and the Manusmriti mention various forms of village assemblies"},{"type":"normal","text":"First, Mahatma Gandhi’s vision of ‘Gram Swaraj’ (Village Self-Rule) was a powerful inspiration. Gandhi believed that India’s villages should be self-sufficient and self-governing, with the village rep"},{"type":"normal","text":"Second, the Community Development Programme (1952) and the National Extension Service (1953) were launched to promote rural development through community participation. However, these programmes faile"},{"type":"normal","text":"Fourth, the Ashok Mehta Committee (1978) recommended a two-tier system (Zilla Parishad and Mandal Panchayat), direct elections, reservation for SCs and STs, and constitutional protection for Panchayat"}]},{"id":"sec_345","title":"42.2 Key Provisions of the 73rd Amendment","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The 73rd Constitutional Amendment Act, 1992 (effective from 24 April 1993), added Part IX (Articles 243 to 243O) and the Eleventh Schedule to the Constitution. The key provisions are:"},{"type":"normal","text":"Article 243A provides for a Gram Sabha, which is a body consisting of persons registered in the electoral rolls relating to a village comprised within the area of Panchayat at the village level. The G"},{"type":"normal","text":"Article 243B provides for the constitution of Panchayats at the village, intermediate, and district levels in every State. A State having a population not exceeding twenty lakhs may not have Panchayat"},{"type":"normal","text":"Article 243C provides for the composition of Panchayats. All seats in a Panchayat are to be filled by persons chosen by direct election from territorial constituencies. The Chairperson of a Panchayat "},{"type":"normal","text":"Article 243D provides for the reservation of seats. Seats shall be reserved for Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes in every Panchayat in proportion to their population. Not less than one-third of t"},{"type":"normal","text":"Article 243E fixes the duration of every Panchayat at five years from the date of its first meeting. Elections to constitute a Panchayat must be completed before the expiry of its duration. If a Panch"},{"type":"normal","text":"Article 243G provides that the Legislature of a State may, by law, endow the Panchayats with such powers and authority as may be necessary to enable them to function as institutions of self-government"},{"type":"normal","text":"Article 243H provides that the Legislature of a State may, by law, authorise a Panchayat to levy, collect, and appropriate taxes, duties, tolls, and fees; assign to a Panchayat the taxes, duties, toll"},{"type":"normal","text":"Article 243-I provides for the constitution of a State Finance Commission every five years (or earlier) to review the financial position of the Panchayats and to make recommendations regarding the dis"},{"type":"normal","text":"Article 243-K provides for the superintendence, direction, and control of the preparation of electoral rolls for, and the conduct of, elections to the Panchayats to be vested in a State Election Commi"}]},{"id":"sec_346","title":"42.3 PESA Act, 1996","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Panchayats (Extension to Scheduled Areas) Act (PESA), 1996, extends a modified version of the 73rd Amendment to the Scheduled Areas listed under the Fifth Schedule. The Act is based on the princip"}]},{"id":"ch_347","title":"CHAPTER 43","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_348","title":"India’s Anti-Corruption Framework","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_349","title":"43.1 Prevention of Corruption Act, 1988","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Prevention of Corruption Act (PCA), 1988 (as amended in 2018), is the primary anti-corruption law in India. It replaced the Prevention of Corruption Act, 1947. The Act defines ‘public servant’ bro"},{"type":"normal","text":"The Prevention of Corruption (Amendment) Act, 2018, made significant changes: it criminalised the act of giving a bribe (not just receiving one – previously, only the bribe-taker was liable), introduc"}]},{"id":"sec_350","title":"43.2 The Central Vigilance Commission","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Central Vigilance Commission (CVC) was established in 1964 by an executive resolution of the Government of India, based on the recommendations of the Santhanam Committee on Prevention of Corruptio"},{"type":"normal","text":"The CVC supervises the functioning of the Central Bureau of Investigation (CBI) in cases involving corruption by public servants. It exercises superintendence over the vigilance administration of vari"}]},{"id":"sec_351","title":"43.3 The Central Bureau of Investigation","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Central Bureau of Investigation (CBI) is the premier investigating agency of the Government of India. It was established in 1963 by a resolution of the Ministry of Home Affairs, to investigate cor"},{"type":"normal","text":"A critical limitation of the CBI is that it can investigate offences in a State only with the consent of the State Government (under Section 6 of the DSPE Act) or on the order of a court (the Supreme "}]},{"id":"sec_352","title":"43.4 The Whistle Blowers Protection Act, 2014","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Whistle Blowers Protection Act, 2014, was enacted to protect persons who make disclosures about allegations of corruption, wilful misuse of power, or commission of a criminal offence by a public s"}]},{"id":"sec_353","title":"43.5 Benami Transactions (Prohibition) Act","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Benami Transactions (Prohibition) Amendment Act, 2016 (amending the original 1988 Act), provides for the prohibition of benami transactions (transactions in which property is held by one person bu"}]},{"id":"ch_354","title":"CHAPTER 44","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_355","title":"Additional Detailed Revision Tables (26–50)","level":1,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: 27. Speaker of Lok Sabha – Key Facts"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: 28. CAG – Detailed Facts"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: 29. Finance Commission – Key Facts"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: 30. Comparison of Parliamentary Motions"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: 31. Important Constitutional Keywords and Definitions"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: 32. Grounds for Disqualification of MPs/MLAs"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: 33. Important Amendments and Their Numbers"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: 34. UPSC Prelims: Most Frequently Tested Topics"}]},{"id":"ch_356","title":"CHAPTER 45","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_357","title":"Indian Federalism: Detailed Critical Analysis","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_358","title":"45.1 The Nature of Indian Federalism","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The question of whether India is truly a federal state has been debated since the adoption of the Constitution. The Constitution itself does not use the word ‘federation’ anywhere; Article 1 describes"},{"type":"normal","text":"Constitutional scholars have offered various characterisations of the Indian federal system. K.C. Wheare described it as ‘quasi-federal’ – a unitary state with subsidiary federal features rather than "}]},{"id":"sec_359","title":"45.2 Federal Features of the Constitution","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Indian Constitution exhibits several quintessential federal features. First, it is a written and rigid constitution (at least for provisions affecting the federal structure, which require special "}]},{"id":"sec_360","title":"45.3 Unitary Features of the Constitution","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Despite the federal features, the Indian Constitution has a pronounced unitary tilt. The following features make it significantly different from classical federal systems like the United States or Aus"},{"type":"normal","text":"First, the Centre has a disproportionately large share of legislative power. The Union List contains 97 subjects (the most important ones, including defence, foreign affairs, banking, communications, "},{"type":"normal","text":"Second, the states do not have their own separate constitution (unlike the states in the US, which each have their own constitution). The Constitution of India provides for the governance of both the "},{"type":"normal","text":"Fifth, All-India Services (IAS, IPS, IFS) serve both the Centre and the States, ensuring that the Centre has administrative influence in the States. Sixth, Governors are appointed by the Centre and se"},{"type":"normal","text":"Eighth, the power to create new states, alter boundaries, and change names of states lies with the Union Parliament (Article 3), which can do so by a simple majority, without even requiring the consen"}]},{"id":"sec_361","title":"45.4 Trends in Indian Federalism","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Indian federalism has evolved significantly since 1950. In the initial decades (1950s–1960s), the dominance of the Indian National Congress at both the Centre and in most States meant that Centre-Stat"},{"type":"normal","text":"The era of coalition politics (1989–2014) saw a gradual strengthening of States’ bargaining power. Regional parties gained prominence and played king-maker roles at the Centre. The Inter-State Council"},{"type":"normal","text":"The introduction of GST through the 101st Amendment (2016) represented both a pooling of sovereignty (as States surrendered their independent power to levy indirect taxes) and a cooperative mechanism "},{"type":"normal","text":"The concept of ‘competitive federalism’ has gained prominence in recent years, where States compete with each other to improve governance outcomes. NITI Aayog’s indices (such as the Health Index, Scho"}]},{"id":"sec_362","title":"45.5 Inter-State River Water Disputes","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Inter-state river water disputes have been one of the most contentious issues in Indian federalism. Article 262 empowers Parliament to provide for the adjudication of disputes relating to the use, dis"}]},{"id":"ch_363","title":"CHAPTER 46","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_364","title":"Elections and Representation: Advanced Topics","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_365","title":"46.1 Electoral Reforms","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Electoral reform has been a continuous process in India. The Election Commission, the Law Commission, and various parliamentary committees have recommended numerous reforms. Some of the key reforms th"},{"type":"normal","text":"Several reform proposals remain unimplemented or are under discussion. These include: simultaneous elections (‘One Nation One Election’) – the Ram Nath Kovind Committee (2023) recommended holding Lok "}]},{"id":"sec_366","title":"46.2 The Model Code of Conduct","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Model Code of Conduct (MCC) is a set of guidelines issued by the Election Commission for political parties, candidates, and the government during the election period. The MCC comes into effect fro"},{"type":"normal","text":"The MCC covers several areas: general conduct (parties should not appeal to caste or communal feelings; no bribery, intimidation, or impersonation); meetings and processions (parties must inform the p"},{"type":"normal","text":"The Supreme Court, in S. Subramaniam Balaji v. Government of Tamil Nadu (2013), held that the promise of freebies in election manifestos does not violate the Representation of the People Act. However,"}]},{"id":"sec_367","title":"46.3 Registration and Recognition of Political Parties","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Political parties in India are registered with the Election Commission under Section 29A of the Representation of the People Act, 1951. Registered parties are classified as either ‘recognised’ or ‘unr"},{"type":"normal","text":"As of 2024, there are six National Parties: the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP), the Indian National Congress (INC), the Bahujan Samaj Party (BSP), the Communist Party of India (Marxist) (CPI(M)), the Na"}]},{"id":"sec_368","title":"46.4 Electoral Bonds and Political Funding","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Electoral Bond Scheme was introduced in 2018 through an amendment to the Finance Act, 2017. Electoral bonds were bearer instruments (like promissory notes) that could be purchased from authorised "}]},{"id":"ch_369","title":"CHAPTER 47","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_370","title":"Miscellaneous Important Topics for UPSC Prelims","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_371","title":"47.1 Article 370 and the Reorganisation of Jammu and Kashmir","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Article 370 of the Constitution granted a special status to the erstwhile State of Jammu and Kashmir, providing it with a degree of autonomy not enjoyed by other States. Under Article 370, the provisi"},{"type":"normal","text":"On 5 August 2019, the President of India issued a Presidential Order (C.O. 272) under Article 370(1), effectively replacing the 1954 Presidential Order and making all provisions of the Indian Constitu"}]},{"id":"sec_372","title":"47.2 The Goods and Services Tax (GST)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Goods and Services Tax (GST) was introduced by the 101st Constitutional Amendment Act, 2016, and came into effect on 1 July 2017. GST is a comprehensive, multi-stage, destination-based indirect ta"},{"type":"normal","text":"The GST Council (Article 279A) is the constitutional body that makes recommendations on GST rates, exemptions, threshold limits, model laws, and any other matter relating to GST. It consists of the Un"}]},{"id":"sec_373","title":"47.3 The Women’s Reservation Bill (106th Amendment)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Constitution (106th Amendment) Act, 2023, provides for the reservation of one-third of all seats in the Lok Sabha and State Legislative Assemblies for women. This includes one-third of the seats r"}]},{"id":"sec_374","title":"47.4 The National Education Policy, 2020","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"While not a constitutional topic per se, the National Education Policy (NEP) 2020 is relevant for UPSC Prelims because it relates to Fundamental Rights (Article 21A – Right to Education) and Directive"}]},{"id":"sec_375","title":"47.5 Tribunals and Alternative Dispute Resolution","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The 42nd Amendment Act of 1976 added Articles 323A and 323B to the Constitution, providing for the establishment of tribunals. Article 323A empowers Parliament to establish Administrative Tribunals fo"},{"type":"normal","text":"In L. Chandra Kumar v. Union of India (1997), the Supreme Court held that the jurisdiction of the High Courts under Articles 226 and 227 cannot be completely excluded by tribunals. While tribunals can"},{"type":"normal","text":"Alternative Dispute Resolution (ADR) mechanisms include Lok Adalats (established under the Legal Services Authorities Act, 1987 – the award of a Lok Adalat is deemed to be a decree of a civil court an"}]},{"id":"sec_376","title":"47.6 The Uniform Civil Code (Article 44)","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"Article 44 of the Directive Principles directs the State to endeavour to secure for the citizens a Uniform Civil Code (UCC) throughout the territory of India. The UCC would replace the personal laws o"}]},{"id":"ch_377","title":"CHAPTER 48","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_378","title":"Final Comprehensive Revision: Key Takeaways","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_379","title":"48.1 Ten Most Important Constitutional Articles for UPSC Prelims","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"trap","text":"Based on analysis of previous years’ UPSC Prelims questions, the ten most important constitutional articles are: Article 14 (Equality before law – classification test, arbitrariness test), Article 19 (Six freedoms and their restrictions), Article 21 (Life and personal liberty – due process, expanded"}]},{"id":"sec_380","title":"48.2 Ten Most Important Supreme Court Cases for UPSC Prelims","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The ten most important Supreme Court cases for UPSC Prelims are: Kesavananda Bharati v. State of Kerala (1973) – Basic Structure Doctrine; Maneka Gandhi v. Union of India (1978) – Due process under Ar"}]},{"id":"sec_381","title":"48.3 Ten Most Important Constitutional Amendments for UPSC Prelims","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The ten most important Constitutional Amendments are: 1st Amendment (1951) – Article 15(4), Ninth Schedule, restrictions on free speech; 42nd Amendment (1976) – ‘Mini Constitution’ – most extensive ch"}]},{"id":"sec_382","title":"48.4 Final Words of Advice for UPSC Aspirants","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"trap","text":"Indian Polity is one of the most scoring subjects in UPSC Prelims, but it requires precision rather than mere familiarity. The UPSC often tests fine distinctions – between the President and the Governor, between Article 32 and Article 226, between Money Bills and ordinary bills, between constitution"},{"type":"normal","text":"Revision is key. The revision tables in this book are designed to help you quickly recall critical facts and distinctions. Make it a habit to revise these tables at least once a week in the months lea"},{"type":"normal","text":"Remember that UPSC Prelims questions on Polity increasingly test current developments – recent Supreme Court judgments, new constitutional amendments, and ongoing governance debates. Stay updated with"},{"type":"normal","text":"We wish you the very best in your UPSC journey. May this comprehensive guide serve as your trusted companion in mastering Indian Polity and Governance for the Civil Services Preliminary Examination."},{"type":"normal","text":"─── END OF BOOK ───"}]},{"id":"ch_383","title":"CHAPTER 49","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_384","title":"Contemporary Constitutional Controversies","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_385","title":"49.1 The Money Bill Controversy","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The distinction between Money Bills and ordinary bills has become one of the most contentious constitutional issues in recent years. Under Article 110, a bill is deemed to be a Money Bill if it deals "},{"type":"normal","text":"The controversy arose when the Aadhaar (Targeted Delivery of Financial and Other Subsidies, Benefits and Services) Bill, 2016, was passed as a Money Bill. Critics argued that the Aadhaar Bill dealt wi"},{"type":"normal","text":"The Finance Act has also been challenged on similar grounds. The Finance Act, 2017, included provisions relating to the merger and restructuring of various tribunals (such as the Securities Appellate "}]},{"id":"sec_386","title":"49.2 The Governor’s Delay on Bills","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"A growing constitutional controversy concerns the delay by Governors in acting on bills passed by State Legislatures. The Constitution does not prescribe any time limit within which the Governor must "},{"type":"normal","text":"In State of Punjab v. Principal Secretary to the Governor of Punjab (2023), the Supreme Court addressed this issue and held that the Governor does not have an absolute veto and cannot indefinitely wit"}]},{"id":"sec_387","title":"49.3 The Debate on Simultaneous Elections","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The idea of holding simultaneous elections to the Lok Sabha and all State Legislative Assemblies (commonly referred to as ‘One Nation One Election’) has been debated for several decades. India held si"},{"type":"normal","text":"The Ram Nath Kovind Committee, constituted in 2023 (headed by former President Ram Nath Kovind), submitted its report recommending a phased approach to simultaneous elections: Phase 1 would synchronis"},{"type":"normal","text":"Arguments in favour of simultaneous elections include: reduction in election expenditure (both for the government and political parties); reduction in the frequency of the Model Code of Conduct, which"}]},{"id":"sec_388","title":"49.4 The Freebies Debate","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The debate over ‘freebies’ in election manifestos has gained constitutional significance in recent years. In Ashwini Kumar Upadhyay v. Union of India (2022), the Supreme Court took note of the growing"}]},{"id":"ch_389","title":"CHAPTER 50","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_390","title":"Indian Polity in Comparative Perspective","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_391","title":"50.1 India vs USA: Key Differences","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"While the Indian Constitution borrowed several features from the US Constitution (Fundamental Rights, judicial review, impeachment, Preamble), the two systems differ significantly. The US follows a pr"}]},{"id":"sec_392","title":"50.2 India vs UK: Key Differences","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"India’s parliamentary system is modelled on the British Westminster system, but there are significant differences. The UK has an unwritten (uncodified) constitution based on conventions, statutes, and"}]},{"id":"sec_393","title":"50.3 India vs France: Key Differences","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"The Indian Preamble was influenced by the French ideals of Liberty, Equality, and Fraternity (from the French Revolution of 1789 and the French Declaration of the Rights of Man and the Citizen). Howev"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: 35. Comparative Constitutional Features"}]},{"id":"ch_394","title":"CHAPTER 51","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"ch_395","title":"Quick-Reference Article Index","level":1,"paras":[]},{"id":"sec_396","title":"51.1 Articles Most Frequently Tested in UPSC Prelims","level":2,"paras":[{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: 36. Article Quick-Reference (Part I)"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: 37. Article Quick-Reference (Part II)"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: 38. Article Quick-Reference (Part III)"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: 39. Chronological Timeline of Key Constitutional Events"},{"type":"normal","text":"PRELIMS REVISION TABLE: 40. Final Quick Facts: Numbers to Remember"}]}];
